{"title_page": "2022 United States Senate election in California", "text_new": "{{More references|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2022 United States Senate election in California\n| country            = California\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2016 United States Senate election in California\n| previous_year      = 2016\n| next_election      = 2028 United States Senate election in California\n| next_year          = 2028\n| election_date      = November 8, 2022\n| image1             = \n| nominee1           = \n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = \n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| map_image          = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = County results\n| title              = U.S. senator\n| before_election    = [[Kamala Harris]]\n| before_party       = Democratic Party (United States)\n| after_election     = \n| after_party        = \n}}\n{{ElectionsCA}}\n\nThe '''2022 United States Senate election in California''' will be held on November 8, 2022, to elect a member of the [[United States Senate]] to represent the [[California|State of California]].\n\n==Democratic primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Potential====\n* [[Kamala Harris]], incumbent U.S. senator and former [[2020 United States presidential election|2020]] [[President of the United States|presidential]] [[Kamala Harris 2020 presidential campaign|candidate]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Jonathan |last2=Herndon |first2=Astead W. |last3=Burns |first3=Alexander |title=How Kamala Harris\u2019s Campaign Unraveled |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/29/us/politics/kamala-harris-2020.html |website=The New York Times |date=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Steyer]], [[hedge fund]] manager and former [[2020 United States presidential election|2020]] [[President of the United States|presidential]] [[Tom Steyer 2020 presidential campaign|candidate]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Jonathan |last2=Herndon |first2=Astead W. |last3=Burns |first3=Alexander |title=How Kamala Harris\u2019s Campaign Unraveled |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/29/us/politics/kamala-harris-2020.html |website=The New York Times |date=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Republican primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Declared====\n\n====Potential====\n*  [[David Dreier]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], Former Governor\n*  [[Mary Bono]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Dan Lungren]], Former U.S. Representative \n*  [[John Campbell III]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Brian Bilbray]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Jeff Denham]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Steve Knight (politician)|Steve Knight]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Doug Ose]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Mimi Walters]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Darrell Issa]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Tom Campbell]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Ed Royce]], Former U.S. Representative\n*  [[Bruce Jenner]], Olympic Medalist\n*  [[Chris Mitchum]], Actor\n*  [[Abel Maldonado]], Former Lt. Governor\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2022 United States elections}}\n\n[[Category:United States Senate elections in California|2022]]\n[[Category:2022 United States Senate elections|California]]\n[[Category:2022 California elections|United States Senate]]\n", "text_old": "{{More references|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2022 United States Senate election in California\n| country            = California\n| type               = presidential\n| ongoing            = yes\n| previous_election  = 2016 United States Senate election in California\n| previous_year      = 2016\n| next_election      = 2028 United States Senate election in California\n| next_year          = 2028\n| election_date      = November 8, 2022\n| image1             = \n| nominee1           = \n| party1             = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1      = \n| percentage1        = \n| image2             = \n| nominee2           = \n| party2             = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2      = \n| percentage2        = \n| map_image          = \n| map_size           = \n| map_caption        = County results\n| title              = U.S. senator\n| before_election    = [[Kamala Harris]]\n| before_party       = Democratic Party (United States)\n| after_election     = \n| after_party        = \n}}\n{{ElectionsCA}}\n\nThe '''2022 United States Senate election in California''' will be held on November 8, 2022, to elect a member of the [[United States Senate]] to represent the [[California|State of California]].\n\n==Democratic primary==\n===Candidates===\n====Potential====\n* [[Kamala Harris]], incumbent U.S. senator and former [[2020 United States presidential election|2020]] [[President of the United States|presidential]] [[Kamala Harris 2020 presidential campaign|candidate]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Jonathan |last2=Herndon |first2=Astead W. |last3=Burns |first3=Alexander |title=How Kamala Harris\u2019s Campaign Unraveled |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/29/us/politics/kamala-harris-2020.html |website=The New York Times |date=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Tom Steyer]], [[hedge fund]] manager and former [[2020 United States presidential election|2020]] [[President of the United States|presidential]] [[Tom Steyer 2020 presidential campaign|candidate]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Jonathan |last2=Herndon |first2=Astead W. |last3=Burns |first3=Alexander |title=How Kamala Harris\u2019s Campaign Unraveled |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/29/us/politics/kamala-harris-2020.html |website=The New York Times |date=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2022 United States elections}}\n\n[[Category:United States Senate elections in California|2022]]\n[[Category:2022 United States Senate elections|California]]\n[[Category:2022 California elections|United States Senate]]\n", "name_user": "2605:e000:1c0c:85ac:a811:3873:85a5:3dd0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 951537948 byMuboshgu(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_United_States_Senate_election_in_California"}
{"title_page": "Little League Baseball", "text_new": "{{hatnote|See: [[Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball|Intermediate, Junior, and Senior League Baseball]]}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| title          = Little League Baseball, Incorporated\n| upcoming_season= 2019 Little League World Series\n| logo           = Little League Baseball - Logo.jpg\n| sport          = [[Baseball]], [[softball]]\n| founded        = {{Baseball year|1939}} in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania|Williamsport]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States of America|U.S.]]\n| fame           = Largest organized youth sports organization in the world\n| motto          = Courage, Character, and Loyalty\n| inaugural      = 1939\n| competitors    = 2,600,000\n| teams          = over 180,000\n| Leagues        = approximately 7,500\n| qualification  = [[2019 Little League World Series qualification|Little League International Tournament]]\n| website        = {{URL|http://www.Littleleague.org/}}\n| ceo            = Stephen D. Keener\n| director       = David Houseknecht, [[Chief Financial Officer|CFO]]\n| coo            = Patrick Wilson\n| tv             = [[ESPN]], [[ESPN2]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]; [[Madison Square Garden Network]] (MSG), [[New England Sports Network]] (NESN)\n| founder        = [[Carl E. Stotz]], George Bebble, Bert Bebble\n}}\n'''Little League Baseball and Softball''' (officially, '''Little League Baseball Inc'''<ref name= corp/>) is a [[501(c)(3)]] [[nonprofit organization]]<ref name= irseos>\"[https://apps.irs.gov/app/eos/displayAll.do?dispatchMethod=displayAllInfo&Id=4564989&ein=231688231&country=US&deductibility=all&dispatchMethod=searchAll&isDescending=false&city=&ein1=23-1688231&postDateFrom=&exemptTypeCode=al&submitName=Search&sortColumn=orgName&totalResults=1&names=&resultsPerPage=25&indexOfFirstRow=0&postDateTo=&state=All+States Little League Baseball Inc, EIN: 23-1688231]\". ''Tax Exempt Organization Search''. [[Internal Revenue Service]]. Retrieved August 22, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.guidestar.org/FinDocuments/2017/231/688/2017-231688231-0efaa9bf-9.pdf Form 990: Return of Organization Exempt from Income Tax]\". ''Little League Baseball Incorporated''. [[Guidestar]]. September 30, 2017.</ref> based in [[South Williamsport, Pennsylvania]], [[United States of America|United States]], that organizes local youth [[baseball]] and [[softball]] [[sports league|leagues]] throughout the United States and the rest of the world.\n\nFounded by [[Carl Stotz]], George Bebble, and Bert Bebble in 1939 as a three-team league in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]], and formally incorporated on October 10, 1950,<ref name= corp>\"[https://www.corporations.pa.gov/search/CorpSearch Little League Baseball Inc]\". ''Corporation Search''. Pennsylvania Department of State. Retrieved August 22, 2018.</ref> Little League Baseball encourages local volunteers to organize and operate Little League programs that are annually chartered through Little League International. Each league can structure itself to best serve the children in the area in which the league operates. Several specific divisions of Little League baseball and softball are available to children ages 4 to 16. The organization holds a [[congressional charter]] under [[Title 36 of the United States Code]].<ref>Section 130501(a) of [[Title 36 of the United States Code]] provides that Little League Baseball, Incorporated is a [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/36/130501 \"federally chartered corporation\"].</ref>\n\nThe organization's administrative office is located in South Williamsport, Pennsylvania. The first Little League Baseball World Series was played in Williamsport in 1947. The Little League International Complex hosts the annual [[Little League Baseball World Series]] at [[Howard J. Lamade Stadium]] and [[Little League Volunteer Stadium]], and is also the site of the [[Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum]], which provides a history of Little League Baseball and Softball through interactive exhibits for children. Many [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) players played in Little League.\n\n==History==\nCarl Stotz, a resident of Williamsport, Pennsylvania, founded Little League Baseball in 1939. He began experimenting with his idea in the summer of 1938 when he gathered Carl's nephews, Jimmy and Major Gehron and their neighborhood friends. They tried different field dimensions over the course of the summer and played several informal games. The following summer they felt that they were ready to establish what later became Little League Baseball. The first league in Williamsport had just three teams, each sponsored by a different business. The first teams, Jumbo Pretzel, Lycoming Dairy, and Lundy Lumber, were managed by Carl Stotz, and brothers George and Bert Bebble. The men, joined by their wives and another couple, formed the first-ever Little League Board of Directors.<ref name=\"llbhistory\">{{cite web |url = http://www.littleleague.org/about/history.asp |title = History of Little League |accessdate = 2007-06-26 |publisher = Little League |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070514082459/http://www.littleleague.org/about/history.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-05-14}}</ref>\n\nThe first League game took place on June 6, 1939. Lundy Lumber defeated Lycoming Dairy, 23\u20138. Lycoming Dairy came back to claim the league [[championship]]. They, the first-half-season champions, defeated Lundy Lumber, the second-half champs, in a best-of-three season-ending [[playoff format|series]]. The following year a second league was formed in Williamsport, and from there Little League Baseball grew to become an international organization of nearly 200,000 teams in every U.S. state and over 80 countries around the world.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\nFrom 1951 through 1973, Little League was for boys only. In 1974, Little League [[Regulation of sport|rules]] were revised to allow participation by girls in the baseball program following the result of a lawsuit filed by the [[National Organization for Women]] on behalf of [[Maria Pepe]].<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/About_Our_Organization/historyandmission/chronology.htm Little League: History and Mission: Chronology] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224170800/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/About_Our_Organization/historyandmission/chronology.htm |date=2009-02-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"mario_pepe_bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/05_2004/04mariapepeopening.htm|title=Little League World Series Opening Ceremony to Mark 30th Anniversary of Decision Allowing Girls to Play|date=August 9, 2004|accessdate=2009-09-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607002311/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/05_2004/04mariapepeopening.htm|archivedate=June 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, Robert Francis Morrison filed an official charter with Little League Baseball, Incorporated to admit the Cannon Street Y.M.C.A., as its first all-black team.  The league consisted of four teams, sponsored by prominent black businesses in [[Charleston, South Carolina]].<ref name=\"Sport in American History\">{{Cite news|url=https://ussporthistory.com/2014/09/01/baseball-dreams-deferred-the-story-of-the-cannon-street-y-m-c-a-all-stars-part-two/|title=Baseball Dreams Deferred: The Story of the Cannon Street Y.M.C.A. All Stars (Part Two)|date=2014-09-02|work=Sport in American History|access-date=2018-08-20|language=en-US}}</ref> In 1955, when Morrison entered the Cannon Street All-Stars into the city tournament, white leagues reacted by drafting a resolution requesting a whites-only tournament.  All 55 white teams eventually withdrew from the city and state tournament.  The Cannon Street All-Stars became the 1955 South Caroline state champions by forfeit.  However, they were informed by Little League president, Peter J. McGovern, that they would not be permitted to represent the state at the regional championships in Williamsport, GA. Little League executives invited the Cannon Street All-Stars to attend the tournament as guests to view the World Series that they were not permitted to play in.<ref name=\"Sport in American History\"/>\n\nAccording to the Little League Baseball and Softball participation statistics following the 2008 season, there were nearly 2.6 million players in Little League Baseball worldwide, including both boys and girls, including 400,000 registered in softball (also including both boys and girls). For tournament purposes, Little League Baseball is divided into 16 geographic regions; eight National and eight international. Each summer, Little League operates seven World Series tournaments at various locations throughout the U.S. (Little League softball and Junior, Senior, and Big League baseball and softball).\n\n===Timeline===\n\n====Early years====\n'''1939''': Little League is established by [[Carl E. Stotz]]. The first season is played in a lot close to [[Bowman Field (stadium)|Bowman Field]]. Lycoming Dairy is the first season champion.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1946''': Little League has expanded to 12 leagues, all in Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1947''': The first league outside of Pennsylvania is founded in [[Hammonton, New Jersey]]. Maynard League of Williamsport defeats a team from [[Lock Haven, Pennsylvania]] to win the first Little League World Series. [[Allen Yearick]] is the first Little League graduate to play professional baseball when he is signed by the [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1948''': Little League has grown to include 94 leagues. Lock Haven returns to the Little League World Series and defeats a league from [[St. Petersburg, Florida]]. The first corporate sponsor, [[U.S. Rubber]], is announced,<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>  who donate [[Pro-Keds]] shoes to teams at the Little League World Series.<ref name=\"geist\">{{cite book | last = Geist | first = Bill | title = Little League Confidential: One Coach's Completely Unauthorized Tale of Survival | year = 1999 | edition = 1st | publisher = Dell | location = New York | isbn = 0-440-50877-0 }}</ref>\n\n'''1949''': Little League is featured in the ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]'' and on [[newsreel]]s. Carl Stotz gets hundreds of requests for information on how to form leagues at the local level from all over the United States. Little League incorporates in New York.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1950 or 1951''' (sources contradict) Kathryn 'Kay' Johnston -Massar became the first girl to play Little League baseball. Her mother cut her braids and she dressed like a boy. Not knowing what to call herself, she adopted the nickname \"Tubby\" because of her love of Little Lulu comic books, and joined the Kings Dairy Little League team in Corning, N.Y., posing as a boy.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/blog/big_league_stew/post/Katie-Reyes-becomes-first-girl-gamewinner-at-Lit?urn=mlb-185105 Katie Reyes becomes first girl gamewinner at Little League WS - Big League Stew - MLB Blog - Yahoo! Sports]. Sports.yahoo.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref> After earning her way onto the team and being assigned first base, she told her coach she was a girl, but he said \"That's O.K., you're a darned good player.\" Kay, aka 'Tubby' (which all her teammates continued to call her even after they knew the truth), played first base for the season, but was forced to quit after just one season because a new rule, known as the ''Tubby Rule, was created. It'' declared, \"Rule III (f) Girls are not eligible under any circumstances.\"; that rule was in force until 1974.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/08/20/sports/baseball-one-more-pitch-for-first-girl-in-little-league.html | work=The New York Times | first=Neil | last=Amdur | title=BASEBALL; One More Pitch for First Girl in Little League | date=2001-08-20}}</ref>\n\n'''1951''': Leagues are formed in [[British Columbia]], Canada and near the Panama Canal making them the first leagues outside the United States.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1953''': The Little League World Series is televised for the first time. [[Jim McKay]] provides the play by play for [[CBS]]. [[Howard Cosell]] provides play by play for [[Citadel Media|ABC Radio]]. [[Joey Jay]] of [[Middletown, Connecticut]] and the [[Milwaukee Braves]] is the first Little League graduate to play in the [[Major League Baseball|Major Leagues]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1954''': [[Boog Powell]], who later played for the [[Baltimore Orioles]] plays in the Little League World Series for [[Lakeland, Florida]]. [[Ken Hubbs]], who later played for the [[Chicago Cubs]], plays in the Little League World Series for [[Colton, California]]. Little League has expanded to more than 3,300 leagues.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> Jim Barberi who later played for the Los Angeles Dodgers and in a Major League World Series was also a member of the [[Schenectady, New York]] team who won the 1954 Series.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''1955''': There is a Little League organization in each of the 48 U.S. States. [[George W. Bush]] begins playing Little League as a [[catcher]] for the Cubs of the Central Little League in [[Midland, Texas]]. He is the first Little League graduate to be elected President of the United States.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>  The all-black Cannon Street YMCA All-Stars in [[Charleston, South Carolina]] created an uproar that every other Little League organization in South Carolina refused to play Cannon Street.  Little League sent an ultimatum that the team be able to play, which the other leagues refused, where the other 61 organizations returned their charters and formed their own league in response.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/10/30/8098327/little-leagues-civil-war-in-55-a-black-allstar-team-was-sidelined-by-a-racial-boycott-in-south-carolina|title=LITTLE LEAGUE'S CIVIL WAR IN '55 A BLACK ALL-STAR TEAM WAS SIDELINED BY A RACIAL BOYCOTT IN SOUTH CAROLINA|work=Vault|access-date=2018-08-20|language=en}}</ref>  No team from the state had made the tournament until 2015.\n\n'''1956''': Carl Stotz severs his ties with Little League Baseball in a dispute over the direction and control of Little League. Stotz believed the league was becoming over-commercialized by Little League president, Peter J. McGovern.<ref name=stotzbio>{{cite web|title=Carl Edwin Stotz|url=http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Stotz__Carl.html|publisher=Pennsylvania Center for the Book|accessdate=17 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218234504/http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Stotz__Carl.html|archivedate=18 February 2015}}</ref> Stotz remains active in youth baseball with the \"Original League\" in Williamsport.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> Little League records its first on-field death in [[Garland, Texas]] as 12-year-old Richard \"Rick\" Oden is hit in the head by a pitch thrown by Jerry Armstrong.  The city park location of the incident is renamed \"Rick Oden Field.\"  As batting helmets are yet to be developed, Garland teams finish the season wearing youth football helmets over their baseball caps when batting.  Later that year, Fred Shapiro throws a perfect game in the Little League World Series.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n====International era====\n[[File:RiceAmbMrsKellyLittleLeagueCut 600.jpg|thumb|right|250px|U.S. Secretary of State [[Condoleezza Rice]] poses with Little Leaguers from Chile in [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]]]]\n'''1957''': Angel Macias throws a perfect game and [[Monterrey, Mexico|Monterrey]], Mexico, becomes the first team from outside the United States to win the Little League World Series. (Portrayed in 2010 film \"[[The Perfect Game]]\".)<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1959''': The Little League World Series moves from Williamsport to the newly built Little League Headquarters in [[South Williamsport, Pennsylvania|South Williamsport]]. The protective baseball [[batting helmet|helmet]] is developed by Dr. Creighton J. Hale.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1960''': A team from [[West Berlin]], [[West Germany]], is the first team from Europe to play in the Little League World Series. The series is broadcast live for the first time on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. Little League has grown to 27,400 teams in more than 5,500 leagues.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1961''': [[Brian Sipe]], future [[quarterback]] for the [[Cleveland Browns]], plays for the series champions from [[El Cajon, California]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1962''': [[Jackie Robinson]] attends the Little League World Series. President [[John F. Kennedy]] proclaims National Little League Week.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1967''': A team from West Tokyo, Japan, is the first team from Asia to win the Little League World Series.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1969''': Taiwan begins a dominant era that would see them win 17 Little League World Series titles.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1971''': The aluminum baseball bat is first used. It was partly developed by Little League Baseball. [[Lloyd McClendon]] of [[Gary, Indiana|Gary]], Indiana, dominates the Little League World Series, hitting five [[home run]]s in five at-bats. He later played in the Major Leagues and become the first Little League graduate to manage an MLB club with the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1973''': [[Ed Vosberg]] plays in the Little League World Series for [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], Arizona. He later played in the [[College World Series]] for the [[University of Arizona]] in 1980 and the [[World Series]] in 1997 for the [[Florida Marlins]]. Vosberg is the first person to have played in all three world series.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1974''': Girls are formally permitted to play in the Little League Baseball program as result of lawsuit brought on behalf of Frances Pescatore<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.si.com/vault/1974/04/22/614696/now-georgy-porgy-runs-away/ | work=CNN | title=Now Georgy-porgy Runs Away | date=1974-04-22 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019035438/http://www.si.com/vault/1974/04/22/614696/now-georgy-porgy-runs-away | archivedate=2015-10-19 }}</ref> and [[Jenny Fulle]],<ref>{{cite news|title=No More Discrimination / Little League Relents, Votes To Allow Girls To Play Ball|newspaper=The Marin Independent Journal|date=June 13, 1974|page=14}}</ref> and a Little League Softball program for both boys and girls is created. Bunny Taylor becomes the first girl to pitch a no-hitter.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/page2/s/list/moments/uswomen.html ESPN.com - Page2 - Greatest U.S. women's sports moments]. Espn.go.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n\n'''1975''': In a controversial decision, all foreign teams are banned from the Little League World Series. International play is restored the following year.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1980''': A team from [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida, representing Belmont Heights Little League, is led by two future major leaguers [[Derek Bell (baseball)|Derek Bell]] and [[Gary Sheffield]]. Bell returns the following year and Belmont Heights again loses in the finals to a team from Taiwan.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1982''': The Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum opens. Cody Webster leads a team from [[Kirkland, Washington]], in an upset victory of a powerful team from Taiwan. It was Taiwan's first loss in 31 games.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> This game was later featured on ESPN's [[30 for 30]] series ''Little Big Men.''\n\n'''1984''': [[Seoul]], South Korea, wins the first title for a South Korean team. They defeat a team from [[Altamonte Springs, Florida]], led by future [[Boston Red Sox]] catcher, [[Jason Varitek]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1984:''': Victoria Roche, a 12-year-old from Belgium, becomes the first girl to play in the Little League World Series.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/espnw/title-ix/timeline/ Timeline - espnW] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605065812/http://espn.go.com/espnw/title-ix/timeline/ |date=2012-06-05 }}. Espn.go.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n\n'''1988''': [[Tom Seaver]] is the first former Little Leaguer to be enshrined in the Peter J. McGovern Museum Hall of Excellence.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1989''': Poland becomes the first former [[Warsaw Pact]] nation to receive a Little League charter. [[Trumbull, Connecticut]], led by future [[National Hockey League|NHL]] star [[Chris Drury]], wins the Little League World Series.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1991''': Future NL All Star [[Jason Marquis]] pitches the Staten Island South Shore Little League team to third place in the Little League World Series over Canada, throwing a [[no-hitter]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=1907492 \"World Series may pit former Little League stars against each other,\" ''[[ESPN]]'', 10/25/04, accessed 6/6/07]</ref>\n\n'''1992''': Carl Stotz, the founder of Little League, dies. Lights are installed at Lamade Stadium allowing for the first night games to be played. The series is expanded from single elimination to round-robin format. [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]], California, managed by former Major Leaguer [[Jeff Burroughs]] and led by his son, future Major Leaguer [[Sean Burroughs]], is named series champion after [[Zamboanga City]], Philippines, is forced to forfeit for playing with ineligible players.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1993''': Long Beach repeats as champions, defeating Coquivacoa Little League of [[Maracaibo, Venezuela|Maracaibo]], Venezuela. It is the first U.S. team to successfully defend its title.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1997''': [[ESPN2]] broadcasts regional play for the first time. Taiwan's baseball association withdraws from Little League Baseball (they would rejoin in 2003) over newly established rules on zoning.  Bradenton, Florida, and Pottsville, Pennsylvania, play at Lamade Stadium before the largest crowd ever to attend a non-championship game. The crowd was estimated at over 35,000 fans.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1999''': [[Burkina-Faso]] becomes the 100th nation with a Little League organization. Hirkata Little League of [[Osaka]], Japan, becomes the first Japanese team to win a title since 1976.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''2000''': An expansion project begins at Little League International. Volunteer Stadium is built. This allows the <ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> pool of participants to be doubled from 8 to 16 the following year.\n\n'''2001''': The LLWS expands from 8 to 16 teams, with the following changes to regional lineups (post-2000 regions in '''bold'''):\n* US regions:{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n** The East Region splits into the '''New England''' and '''Mid-Atlantic''' Regions.\n** The Central Region splits into the '''Great Lakes''' and '''Midwest''' Regions.\n** The South Region splits into the '''Southeast''' and '''Southwest''' Regions.\n** The '''West''' Region spins off the '''Northwest''' Region.\n* International regions:{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n** '''Canada''' remains intact as a region.\n** The '''Latin America''' Region spins off new regions for the '''Caribbean''' and '''Mexico'''.\n** The Far East Region splits into the '''Asia''' and '''Pacific''' Regions.\n** The '''Europe''' Region spins off the '''TransAtlantic'''<!--This is LL's official spelling.--> Region.\n*** These two regions were geographically identical, differing in the required composition of playing rosters. Transatlantic teams were required to consist of a majority of players who were nationals of the US, Canada, or Japan. Europe teams could have no more than three nationals of those countries.\n\nIn other news, Volunteer Stadium is opened. [[George W. Bush]] becomes the first U.S. president to visit the Little League World Series.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> Led by phenom [[Danny Almonte]], pitching the first perfect game since 1957, the Rolando Paulino All Stars ([[The Bronx|Bronx]], New York) finish third in the series. The team's entire postseason, however, is wiped from the books when it is found that Almonte was 14 years old.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2002''':  [[Austin Dillon]] plays for Southwest Forsyth (County) Little League in [[Clemmons, North Carolina]].  The grandson of [[Richard Childress]], he would win [[NASCAR]] championships in the [[Camping World Truck Series]] in [[2011 NASCAR Camping World Truck Series|2011]] and [[Nationwide Series]] in [[2013 NASCAR Nationwide Series|2013]], and made his [[Sprint Cup Series|Sprint Cup]] debut in [[2014 NASCAR Sprint Cup Series|2014]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2004''': Effective with the 2004 LLWS, the Europe Region is renamed '''EMEA''', for Europe, Middle East, Africa.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2007''': Little League expands into Australia for the first time. Effective with the 2007 LLWS, the Asia and Pacific regions are merged to form the '''Asia-Pacific''' Region, with '''Japan''' being split into its own region.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2007''': Little League expands into [[Kyrgyzstan]] for the first time{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2008''': Effective with this year's LLWS, the Transatlantic and EMEA regions are reorganized into the '''Europe''' and '''Middle East and Africa (MEA)''' regions. The previous nationality restrictions for players from these regions are abolished. Hawai'i wins the 2008 Little League World Series beating Mexico in the Final.\n\n'''2008''': Little League International relocates the Southeast Region Headquarters From Gulfport, Florida, to Warner Robins, Ga. Little League International completes renovation of its administration building in South Williamsport, Pa.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2010''': The World Series tournament is reorganized, eliminating pool play and adopting double-elimination until the bracket winners are determined. Little League announces plans to add a pilot division in baseball for ages 12\u201313 to help baseball Little Leaguers make the transition to regulation-size fields in Junior League Baseball. Bartlett, Illinois, becomes biggest little league.<ref name=pilotdivision>{{cite news |work=Sports Illustrated |date=January 11, 2010 |title=Little League plans new division |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/baseball/mlb/01/11/little.league.division.ap/index.html?xid=si_mlb |accessdate=2010-01-14 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n'''2011''':  The World Series officially eliminates the two four-team brackets and puts all eight teams in the United States bracket and all eight teams in the International bracket, with a [[SEC Baseball Tournament]] style flipped bracket on the loser's bracket to prevent rematches, but does not require the loser to defeat the winner's bracket team twice in either Saturday championship game where the winner advances to the Sunday final.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2012''':\n: The '''Middle East and Africa''' Region produces the first team from the African continent in the Little League World Series: youngsters from Lugazi Little League of [[Uganda]].\n: On August 29, Little League announces a major reorganization of the international brackets, effective with the 2013 LLWS:<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2012/May-Aug/RegionsRealignedfor2013WS.htm |title=Regions Realigned for 2013: Australia to Play in Little League Baseball World Series |publisher=Little League Baseball |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923225531/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2012/May-Aug/RegionsRealignedfor2013WS.htm |archivedate=September 23, 2012 }}</ref>\n:* '''Australia''' spun off from the Asia\u2013Pacific Region and receive its own berth in the LLWS. This reflects Australia's rise to become the fourth-largest country, and largest outside North America, in Little League participation.\n:* The Middle East and Africa Region is disbanded.\n:* Middle Eastern countries, except for Israel and Turkey (which had been in the Europe Region\u2014see below), are placed in the '''Asia\u2013Pacific Region'''.\n:* African countries will be placed in the former Europe Region, which is renamed the '''Europe and Africa Region'''. Israel and Turkey, members of [[Confederation of European Baseball|the European zone]] of the [[International Baseball Federation]],  remains in the renamed region.\n: The Intermediate (50/70) Division, which had operated on a pilot basis since the 2011 season, was announced as an official Little League division, the first new division since 1999. The division, which launched fully in the 2013 season, has the same age limits as standard Little League but extends the pitching rubber to 50 feet from home plate and features bases 70 feet apart. The field is also larger than in standard Little League, and the rules are closer to those of standard baseball.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2013''':\n: Davie Jane Gilmour became the first woman to lead the board of directors for Little League.<ref>[http://psdispatch.com/news/baseball/607398/Gilmour-is-Little-Leagues-first-female-board-chair Gilmour is Little League\u2019s first female board chair - The Sunday Dispatch] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216061154/http://psdispatch.com/news/baseball/607398/Gilmour-is-Little-Leagues-first-female-board-chair |date=December 16, 2013 }}. Psdispatch.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n: The first [[Intermediate League World Series|Intermediate Little League World Series]] is held, in [[Livermore, California]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://intermediateworldseries.org/2013-intermediate-world-series/|title=2013 Intermediate World Series|date=August 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''2014''':\n: On August 15, 2014, [[Mo'ne Davis]] was the first girl in [[Little League World Series]] history to pitch a winning game for the Taney Dragons and earned the win,<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |last1=Rhoden |first1=William C. |title=A Mound Becomes a Summit: Mo'ne Davis Dominates at Little League World Series. South Korea won the world series against Jackie Robinson West. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/16/sports/baseball/mone-davis-dominates-at-little-league-world-series.html?_r=0 |accessdate=August 17, 2014 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 15, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RtrCi94i?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/16/sports/baseball/mone-davis-dominates-at-little-league-world-series.html?_r=1 |archivedate=August 17, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and she was also the first girl to pitch a shutout in Little League postseason history.<ref name=NPR1>{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Emma |title=Mo'ne Davis Throws Like A Girl\u2014At 70 MPH |url=https://www.npr.org/2014/08/16/340912807/mone-davis-throws-like-a-girl-at-70-mph |accessdate=August 17, 2014 |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=August 16, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817183257/http://www.npr.org/2014/08/16/340912807/mone-davis-throws-like-a-girl-at-70-mph |archivedate=August 17, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news |last1=Berg |first1=Ted |title=13-year-old sensation Mo'Ne Davis throws two-hit shutout at Little League World Series |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/08/mone-davis-dominant-llws-pitcher |accessdate=August 17, 2014 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=August 15, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816001858/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/08/mone-davis-dominant-llws-pitcher |archivedate=August 16, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Davis also became the first Little Leaguer to be on the cover of ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' (which she was for the issue dated August 25, 2014.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2014/08/19/mone-davis-sports-illustrated-cover/|title=Little League Star Mo'ne Davis Hits Sports Illustrated's Cover|first=Sam|last=Laird|publisher=|accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> ESPN's coverage of the semifinals game in which Davis played August 20 brought a 3.4 overnight rating, which is an all-time high for Little League on ESPN.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/mone-davis-pitches-record-ratings-726839 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | title=Mo'ne Davis Pitches Record Ratings for Little League World Series | date=2014-08-21}}</ref>\n\n: Jackie Robinson West became the first all-African-American Little League team to win the U.S. championship, but it was later vacated due to violations of the 1997 region regulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/chicago-wins-us-title-little-league-world-series/ng74h/|title=Chicago wins U.S. title in Little League World Series|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3162110/baseball-african-americans-chicago/|title=All Black Team Could Be First to Win Little League World Series|author=Sean Gregory|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/story/_/id/12308988/little-league-strips-chicago-team-us-championship-suspends-coach|title=Little League strips Chicago team of U.S. championship, suspends coach \u2013 ESPN Chicago|work=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\n'''2018''':\nLittle League changes its age rules, moving the birthday deadline from May 1 back to August 31. This allows 13-year-olds to play Majors level this year against 11-year-olds but those 11-year-olds born between May and August will be unable to play next year.<ref>https://www.littleleague.org/news/update-implementation-little-league-baseball-age-determination-date/</ref>\n\n==Regions==\n[[File:2013 Little League Baseball Map.png|thumb|right|600px|Map of Little League regions]]\n{{For|the regions in the other age divisions|Intermediate, Junior, and Senior League Baseball#Regions}}\nThe national regions represented in the annual Little League Baseball World Series are:\n* {{Color box|#BFEFFF}} New England\n* {{Color box|#800080}} Great Lakes\n* {{Color box|#0000CD}} Mid-Atlantic\n* {{Color box|#1C86EE}} Midwest\n* {{Color box|#87CEFA}} Southeast\n* {{Color box|#DDA0DD}} Southwest\n* {{Color box|#000080}} Northwest (including Alaska)\n* {{Color box|#00F5FF}} West (including Hawaii)\nThe international regions are:\n* {{Color box|#FF0000}} Canada<!--spacing, please do not remove-->\n* {{Color box|#FFFF00}} Mexico\n* {{Color box|#00FF00}} Asia-Pacific\n* {{Color box|#008000}} Japan\n* {{Color box|#EE7AE9}} Europe and Africa\n* {{Color box|#FF0080}} Australia\n* {{Color box|#EEC900}} Latin America\n* {{Color box|#EE9A00}} Caribbean\n\n[[Image:Little League World Series and Lamade Stadium.JPG|thumb|550px|center|A Little League World Series game in Howard J. Lamade Stadium in South Williamsport.]]\n\n==Little League World Series==\n[[File:Little League World Series Game 1 crop.jpg|thumb|right|275px|A game of the 2007 Little League World Series]]\nThe best-known event on the Little League Baseball and Softball calendar is the annual [[Little League World Series|Little League Baseball World Series]], which is held every August in [[South Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]. Local and regional tournaments leading up to the World Series are held in the U.S. insular areas of [[Puerto Rico]], the [[U.S. Virgin Islands]], and the [[Northern Mariana Islands]], and throughout the world. In 2003, for example, there were tournaments in Canada, Latin America ([[Mexico]], [[Aruba]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Panama]], [[Peru]], and [[Venezuela]]), Europe (Germany and Poland), and Asia (Japan, [[Philippines]], [[South Korea]], [[Taiwan]]).\n\n===Little, Junior, Senior, and Big League baseball & softball World Series===\nThe Little League Baseball World Series is just one of nine World Series conducted by Little League International every year, each one held in a different location.\n* [[Little League World Series]] (baseball)\n* [[Intermediate League World Series|Intermediate Little League World Series]] (baseball)\n* [[Junior League World Series]] (baseball)\n* [[Senior League World Series]] (baseball)\n* [[Big League World Series]] (baseball) ''(discontinued after 2016)''\n* [[Little League Softball World Series|Girls Little League Softball World Series]] (or the Major Division)<ref name=GirlsSoftballWldSeries>[http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/sbworldseries.htm Softball World Series] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819120316/http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/sbworldseries.htm |date=2017-08-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref>\n* [[Junior League World Series (softball)|Girls Junior League Softball World Series]]\n* Girls Senior League Softball World Series<ref name=GirlsSoftballWldSeries/>\n* Girls Big League Softball World Series<ref name=GirlsSoftballWldSeries/> \n''(discontinued after 2019)''\n1950 1951 1952 1953 1954 1955 1956 1957 1958 1959 1960 1961 1962 1963 1964 1965 1966 1967 1968 1969 1970 1971 1972 1973 1974 1975 1976 1977 1978 1979 1980 1981 1982 1983\n1984 1985 1986 1987 1988 1989 1990 1991 1992 1993 1994 1995 1996 1997 1998 1999 2000\n2001 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009 2010 2011 2012 2013 2014 2015 2016 2017 2018 2019 \n* Boys Little League Softball World Series<ref>\n* 1950 *1951 * 1952 * 1953 * 1954 *1955 *1956 * 1957 *1958 *1959 *1960 *1961 *1962 * * 1963 *1964 * 1965 * 1966 * 1967 *1968 *1969 * 1970 *1971 *1972 *1973 *1974 *1975 * * 1976 *1977 * 1978 * 1979 * 1980 *1981 *1982 * 1983 *1984 *1985 *1986 *1987 *1988 * * 1989 *1990 * 1991 * 1992 * 1993 *1994 *1995 * 1996 *1997 *1998 *1999 *2000 *2001\n* 2002 *2003 * 2004 * 2005 * 2006 *2007 *2008 * 2009 *2010 *2011 *2012 *2013 *2014\n* 2015 *2016 * 2017 * 2018 * 2019\n[http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys/llsbboys.htm Little League Softball (or the Major Division) for Boys] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819120627/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys/llsbboys.htm |date=2017-08-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref>\n* Boys Senior League Softball World Series<ref>\n1950 1951 1952 1953 1954 1955 1956 1957 1958 1959 1960 1961 1962 1963 1964 1965 1966 1967 1968 1969 1970 1971 1972 1973 1974 1975 1976 1977 1978 1979 1980 1981 1982 1983\n1984 1985 1986 1987 1988 1989 1990 1991 1992 1993 1994 1995 1996 1997 1998 1999 2000\n2001 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009 2010 2011 2012 2013 2014 2015 2016 2017\n2018 2019 \n[http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys/slsbboys.htm Senior League Softball for Boys] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819115801/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys/slsbboys.htm |date=2017-08-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref>\n* Boys Big League Softball World Series<ref>\n1970 1971 1972 1973 1974 1975 1976 1977 1978 1979 1980 1981 1982 1983 1984 1985 1986 1987 1988 1989 1990 1991 1992 1993 1994 1995 1996 1997 1998 1999 2000 2001 2002 2003\n2004 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009 2010 2011 2012 2013 2014 2015 2016 2017 2018 2019 \n[http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys/blsbboys.htm Big League Softball for Boys] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127165725/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys/blsbboys.htm |date=2012-01-27 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref> ''(discontinued after 2016)''\n\n==Museum==\n{{main|Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum}}\n\n==Awards==\n:''For winners (by year), see footnote''<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/learn/awards.htm Awards Recognition]. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref>\n{{see also|Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum#Hall of Excellence|Baseball awards#Little League Baseball}}\n* Good Sport of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/goodsportaward.htm Good Sport of the Year Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106143045/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/goodsportaward.htm |date=2009-11-06 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Challenger Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/challengeraward.htm Challenger Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519200918/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/challengeraward.htm |date=2009-05-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* ASAP (A Safety Awareness Program) Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Assets/forms_pubs/asap/AwardsOverview_2010.pdf 2010 ASAP Awards Overview and Past Winners]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (national and regional). Little League. Retrieved 2009-12-06.</ref>\n* Bill Shea Distinguished Little League Graduate Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/distinguishedaward.htm Bill Shea Distinguished Little League Graduate Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826161238/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/distinguishedaward.htm |date=2009-08-26 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Mom of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/momaward.htm Mom of the Year Award.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106134426/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/momaward.htm |date=2009-11-06 }} Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* George and Barbara Bush Little League Parents of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/parentsaward.htm George and Barbara Bush Little League Parents of the Year Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106143054/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/parentsaward.htm |date=2009-11-06 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Volunteer of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/volunteeraward.htm Volunteer of the Year Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724083210/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/volunteeraward.htm |date=2009-07-24 }} Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Howard and Gail Paster Little League Urban Initiative Volunteer of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/uivolunteeraward.htm Howard and Gail Paster Little League Urban Initiative Volunteer of the Year Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091128082939/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/uivolunteeraward.htm |date=2009-11-28 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Howard Hartman Little League Friendship Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2008stories/2008HowardHartmanAwardWinner.htm \"Howard Hartman Award at Little League World Series\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607010523/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2008stories/2008HowardHartmanAwardWinner.htm |date=2011-06-07 }}, Little League Communications Department, August 15, 2008. Little League. Retrieved 2009-12-06.</ref>\n\n==Baseball divisions==\nLittle League Baseball has several baseball divisions for boys, girls  based on age.<ref name=LL_divisions>{{cite web | url = http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/baseball/llbb.htm | title = Little League Baseball (or the Major Division) | author = Little League Baseball, Incorporated | accessdate = May 12, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100508041321/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/baseball/llbb.htm | archive-date = 2010-05-08 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n===Summary chart of major divisions in Little League Baseball===\n{{see also|List of Little League World Series champions by division}}\nThe major divisions of Little League Baseball have their own World Series format as follows:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" | Division\n!scope=\"col\" | Location\n!scope=\"col\" | First Held\n!scope=\"col\" | Age of players\n!scope=\"col\" | Series\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Little League Baseball\n| [[South Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]\n| 1947\n| 9\u201312 years old\n| [[Little League World Series]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Little League Baseball#Little League Intermediate (50/70) Division|Intermediate League Baseball]]\n| [[Livermore, California]]\n| 2013\n| 11\u201313 years old\n| [[Intermediate League World Series]]<!--This is the official name of this level's LLWS.-->\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Junior League Baseball]]\n| [[Taylor, Michigan]]\n| 1981\n| 13\u201314 years old\n| [[Junior League World Series]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball|Senior League Baseball]]\n|[[Easley, South Carolina|Easley]], [[South Carolina]]\n| 1961\n| 14\u201316 years old\n| [[Senior League World Series]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball|Big League Baseball]]\n| [[Easley, South Carolina]]\n| 1968\n| 16\u201318 years old\n| [[Big League World Series]]<BR>''(discontinued after 2016)''\n|}\n\n===Tee-ball===\n<!--Blatant copyright infringement removed; please do not re-add-->\n{{see also|Tee-ball}}\nTee-ball is for boys and girls ages 4\u20135, with local leagues given the option to allow 6\u20137-year-olds to play. In Tee-ball, players hit the ball off of a tee located atop [[home plate]]; live pitching is not allowed. The purpose of the division is to teach young children the basic fundamentals of hitting and fielding.<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Minor leagues===\n<!--Blatant copyright infringement removed; please do not re-add-->\nThe Minor League Baseball division is generally for children ages 7\u201311, with local leagues given the option to allow 6-year-old children to try out. Local leagues are permitted to further divide the Minor League division based on player age and/or experience, and often consist of coach-pitch (i.e., the batter's coach lightly pitching the ball) or machine-pitch at lower levels, with defensive players pitching at higher levels.<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===9\u201310 year olds===\n\"The 9\u201310 Year Old Baseball Division for boys and girls was established as a tournament program in 1994. It gives children of this age the opportunity to experience tournament competition, up to state level. Players on these teams can be chosen from among Major Division and/or Minor Division teams. The diamond used is a 60-foot diamond and the pitching distance is 46 feet.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Little League (or the Major Division)===\n{{see also|Little League World Series}}\n\"The Little League Baseball Division (sometimes known as the Major Division) is for boys and girls ages 9\u201312. A local league may choose to limit its Major Division to 10-, 11-, and 12-year-olds, or 11\u201312-year-olds. The diamond used is a 60-foot diamond and the pitching distance is 46 feet. The local league has an option to choose a Tournament Team (or 'All Stars') of 11\u201312-year-olds from within this division, and the team may enter the International Tournament. The culmination of the International Tournament is the Little League Baseball World Series, featuring teams from around the globe. All expenses for the teams advancing to the World Series (travel, meals, and housing) are paid by Little League Baseball.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Little League Intermediate (50/70) Division===\n{{see also|Intermediate, Junior, and Senior League Baseball}}\nIn 2012, Little League announced plans to add a new division of play for the 2013 season, the Little League Intermediate Division.  This Division is played on a field with a {{convert|50|ft|m|adj=on}} pitching distance and {{convert|70|ft|m|adj=on}} base paths.  It is open to players ages 11\u201313, but may be limited to ages 11\u201312 or 12\u201313 by a local league.  Players in this division are able to lead off and steal. The rules follow rules similar to those of the Junior, Senior, and Big League Divisions of play.\n\nLittle League holds a World Series in this level of play, officially called the [[Intermediate League World Series|Intermediate Little League World Series]], in [[Livermore, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2012/Sep-Dec/LittleLeagueAnnouncesNameofNewBaseballDivisionIntermediate5070.htm|title=Little League Announces Intermediate (50/70) Division|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130415063307/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2012/Sep-Dec/LittleLeagueAnnouncesNameofNewBaseballDivisionIntermediate5070.htm|archivedate=2013-04-15}}</ref>\n\n===Junior League===\n{{main|Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball}}\n\"The Junior League Baseball Division is a program for boys and girls ages 13\u201314, using a conventional {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=on}} diamond with a pitching distance of {{convert|60|ft|6|in|m}}. (A modified diamond is available during the regular season.) The local league has an option to choose a Tournament Team (or \"All Stars\") of 13\u201314-year-olds from within this division (and/or from within the Senior League Division), and the team may enter the International Tournament. The culmination of the International Tournament is the Junior League Baseball World Series, featuring teams from around the globe. All expenses for the teams advancing to the World Series (travel, meals, and housing) are paid by Little League Baseball.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Senior League===\n{{main|Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball}}\n\"The Senior League Baseball Division is for boys and girls 14\u201316 years old, using a conventional {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=on}} diamond with a pitching distance of {{convert|60|ft|6|in|m}}. The local league has an option to choose a Tournament Team (or \"All Stars\") of 14- to 16-year-olds from within this division (and/or from within the Junior League or Big League divisions), and the team may enter the International Tournament. The culmination of the International Tournament is the Senior League Baseball World Series, featuring teams from around the globe. All expenses for the teams advancing to the World Series (travel, meals, and housing) are paid by Little League Baseball.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Big League===\n{{main|Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball}}\n:''Note: The Big League division was discontinued after the [[2016 Big League World Series]].\n\"The Big League Baseball Division is for boys and girls ages 16\u201318, using a conventional {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=on}} diamond with a pitching distance of {{convert|60|ft|6|in|m}}. The local league has an option to choose a Tournament Team (or \"All Stars\") of 16\u201318-year-olds from within this division (and/or from within the Senior League Division), and the team may enter the International Tournament. The culmination of the International Tournament is the Big League Baseball World Series, featuring teams from around the globe. All expenses for the teams advancing to the World Series (travel, meals, and housing) are paid by Little League Baseball.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n==Challenger program==\nLittle League introduced the Challenger Division in 1989 to provide opportunities for children with physical and intellectual challenges to participate in the Little League program.  The Challenger Division utilizes a \"buddy system\" in which Little Leaguers assist Challenger participants in the areas of batting, running and fielding.  Challenger Division games are typically non-competitive in nature.<ref name=LLC_division>\n {{cite web | url = http://www.LittleLeagueChallenger.org | title = Little League Challenger Division| author=Little League Baseball, Incorporated | date = | accessdate=March 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Little League Challenger Division===\nIntroduced in 1989, the Little League Challenger Division is for participants ages 4\u201318.  Games are played on a 46/60 field and are non-competitive.\n\n===Senior League Challenger Division===\nApproved at the 2014 Little League International Congress the Senior League Challenger Division launched in 2015.  This division is for participants ages 15 and above (no maximum age).  Games are played on a 60/90 field and are non-competitive.  Leagues may request permission to play games on a smaller field as well.\n\n===Participation===\nAs of 2018, nearly 1,000 Little Leagues in 10 countries around the world offered the Challenger Program providing an opportunity for more than 31,000 individuals with physical or intellectual challenges to participate in the Little League program.\n\n==Softball divisions==\nLittle League Baseball has several softball divisions for girls and boys, based on age.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" | Division\n!scope=\"col\" | Location\n!scope=\"col\" | First Held\n!scope=\"col\" | Age of players\n!scope=\"col\" | Series\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Little League Softball\n| [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| 1974\n| 9\u201312 years old<ref name=\"littleleague.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/softballdivisions.htm?FullPageView=True|title=Softball \u2013 Divisions of Play|accessdate=31 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913204706/http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/softballdivisions.htm?FullPageView=True|archive-date=2016-09-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| Little League World Series (softball)\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Junior League Softball\n| [[Kirkland, Washington]]\n| 1999\n| 12\u201314 years old<ref name=\"littleleague.org\"/>\n| [[Junior League World Series (softball)]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Senior League Softball\n| [[Sussex County, Delaware]]\n| 1976\n| 13\u201316 years old<ref name=\"littleleague.org\"/>\n| Senior League World Series (softball)\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Big League Softball\n| [[Kalamazoo, Michigan]]\n| 1982\n|14\u201318 years old<ref name=\"littleleague.org\"/>\n| Big League World Series (softball)\n|}\n\n===Boys softball===\n:''See footnote''<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys.htm Boys Softball Divisions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819120356/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys.htm |date=2017-08-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref>\n* Tee Ball Softball for Boys\n* Minor League Softball for Boys\n* Little League Softball (or the Major Division) for Boys\n* Senior League Softball for Boys\n* Big League Softball for Boys\n\n===Girls softball===\n:''See footnotes''<ref name=GirlsSoftballWldSeries/><ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-girls.htm Divisions of Play: Girls Softball Divisions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171219011711/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-girls.htm |date=2017-12-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref><ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/softballdivisions.htm Softball Division: Girls Softball Divisions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221172949/http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/softballdivisions.htm |date=2017-12-21 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref>\n* Girls Tee Ball Softball\n* Girls Minor League Softball\n* Girls Little League Softball (or the Major Division)\n{{see also|Little League Softball World Series}}\n* Girls Junior League Softball\n{{see also|Junior League World Series (softball)}}\n* Girls Senior League Softball\n* Girls Big League Softball\n\n==Rules==\nThe playing rules for the baseball divisions essentially follow the \"[[baseball rules#Codes|Official Baseball Rules]]\" (as defined by and used by [[Major League Baseball]] and published at [http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/official_info/official_rules/foreword.jsp Official Baseball Rules at MLB.com]), especially with respect to the upper divisions (Junior, Senior, and Big League).  Some major exceptions are outlined in the following sections, and these apply to Little League (Minor and Major, ages 7\u201312) except as otherwise noted.\n\n===Rulebooks and fees===\nUnlike Major League Baseball and most other sports such as [[American football|football]], [[soccer]], and [[basketball]], the official rules of Little League Baseball are available to the general public only by online subscription ($20)<ref name=ll_rulebooks>\n {{cite web | url = http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2010/Jan-Apr/2010RedesignedRuleBooksNowAvailable.htm | title = 2010 Redesigned Rule Books Now Available | author = Little League Baseball, Incorporated | date = Jan 5, 2010 | accessdate = May 12, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100511073540/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2010/Jan-Apr/2010RedesignedRuleBooksNowAvailable.htm | archivedate = May 11, 2010 }}</ref> or as a printed edition ($7<ref name=ll_rulebooks/> plus $3 for \"shipping and handling\" within the US via [[United Parcel Service|UPS]]<ref name=ll_rulebook_internet>\n {{cite web | url = http://www.littleleaguestore.net/135.html | title = Little League Store - 2010 Baseball Rule Book | author = Little League Baseball, Incorporated | year = 2010 | accessdate = May 12, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100611213200/http://littleleaguestore.net/135.html | archivedate = June 11, 2010 }}</ref>). In Canada, rulebook orders requested through LittleLeague.ca are routed to the US website at the same prices, except that \"shipping and handling\" to Canada via UPS is US$15.51, for a total of US$22.51 for a single printed copy.<ref name=ll_rulebook_internet/>\n\nRulebooks are not available in sporting goods stores or other stores and must be ordered directly from Little League Baseball, Incorporated or one of its \"Regional Centers\".<ref name=ll_rulebooks/><ref name=Gub>{{cite news | first = Ted | last = Gub | title =  Who's on First? Who Wants to Know, and Why?| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/07/28/AR2007072801205.html | work = Washington Post | page = D1 | date = July 29, 2007 | accessdate = 2008-07-03 | quote = }}</ref>  One paper copy is provided to each team that has sent in an \"Application for Charter and Insurance\",<ref name=ll_rulebooks/> although previously two copies were provided.<ref name=Gub/>\n\nLittle League has been criticized for requiring payment to view its rules.<ref name=Gub/> However, the organization counters by claiming it has been exposed to lawsuits in the past in cases involving organizations not officially affiliated with Little League but which nonetheless use its rules.<ref name=Gub/>\n\n===Length of game===\nA regulation game is 6 [[inning]]s.  If the game is called prior to the completion of six innings, it is considered an official game if four innings have been completed (three and a half, if the home team leads); otherwise, if at least one inning has been completed, it is a suspended game.\n\nIn Intermediate Little League, as well as the Junior, Senior, and Big League levels (ages 13\u201318), a game is seven innings and is official if five innings have been completed.\n\n===Mandatory-play rule===\nIn all divisions except Senior and Big League, every player on the team roster must have at least one plate appearance and play six consecutive outs on defense in each game.  The penalty for a manager violating the rule is a two-game suspension.  This rule is waived if the game is completed prior to the usual duration of the game (six innings in Little League and below, seven innings in Intermediate Little League and Junior League).  This rule is modified during tournament play.  During tournament play, teams that have 13 or more players dressed at the field for a game are mandated to have one (1) \"At Bat\" during the game per player with no defensive requirement.  Teams that have 12 or fewer players dressed at the field for a tournament game require each player to receive one (1) \"At Bat\" plus six consecutive outs played in the field on defense.\n\n===Playing field===\nThe size of the field is dependent on the division of play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mysite.verizon.net/rutherford.ll/rules2.htm|title=Pay Bill, See Offers, Check Email with My Verizon Fios|website=mysite.verizon.net|access-date=2009-01-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531162505/http://mysite.verizon.net/rutherford.ll/rules2.htm|archive-date=2009-05-31|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n'''Tee-ball'''\n:The distance between the bases is generally {{convert|50|ft|m|2}}.\n\n'''Minor League and Little League'''\n:The distance between the bases is {{convert|60|ft|m|2}} and the distance from the [[pitcher's mound]] to home plate is {{convert|46|ft|m|2}}.  Outfield fences must be at least {{convert|165|ft|m}} from home plate, but are usually {{convert|200|ft|m|-1}} or more (the fields at the Williamsport complex have fences 225 feet away).  The bases and pitching rubber are also slightly smaller than in standard baseball.{{Citation needed|reason=The field specification section of littleleague.org does not mention difference in base size|date=April 2014}} Also, unlike fields at almost all levels of competitive baseball for teenagers and adults, the distance between home plate and the outfield fence is constant throughout fair territory.\n\n'''Intermediate Little League'''\n:The distance between the bases is {{convert|70|ft|m|2}} and the distance from the pitcher's mound to home plate is {{convert|50|ft|m|2}}.  The recommended distance between home plate and the outfield fence ranges from {{convert|200|to(-)|275|ft|m|round=5}}; unlike regular Little League, the distances can vary within fair territory.  As in regular Little League, the bases and pitching rubber are also slightly smaller than in standard baseball.\n\n'''Junior League, Senior League, and Big League'''\n:The distance between the bases is {{convert|90|ft|m|2}}, the same as for regulation [[Major League Baseball]] fields. The distance between the pitcher's mound to home plate is {{convert|60.5|ft|m|2}}, also identical to that of MLB. The minimum outfield distance in the upper divisions is {{convert|300|ft|m}} (compare with MLB's official but not strictly enforced minimum of {{convert|325|ft|m|disp=sqbr}} at the foul lines), while the maximum for Big League is {{convert|425|ft|m}}.  (Base paths of {{convert|80|ft|m|2|disp=sqbr}} are optional for Junior League regular season play.)\n\n===Equipment===\n[[File:Little league baseball bunt.JPG|thumb|right|200px|A Little Leaguer executing a bunt]]\n[[Baseball bat|Bats]] (all levels) may be made from wood or other materials (such as [[aluminum]]) and must be approved for use in Little League Baseball.  For the Majors Division and below, the maximum bat length is thirty-three (33) inches (838&nbsp;mm) and barrel diameter may not exceed {{convert|2+1/4|in|mm}}.  Beginning in 2009 all Little League bats must be labeled with a Bat Performance Factor (BPF) of 1.15 or lower.\n\nBats for the Junior League level may have a maximum length of thirty-four (34) inches (864&nbsp;mm) and a maximum barrel diameter of {{convert|2+5/8|in|mm}}.  Bats for the Big and Senior League levels may have a maximum length of thirty-six (36) inches (914&nbsp;mm) and a maximum barrel diameter of {{convert|2+5/8|in|mm}}.  Non-wood Big and Senior League bats must meet the Batted Ball Coefficient of Restitution (BBCOR) testing standards that are currently used in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] and [[National Federation of State High School Associations|NFHS]] (high school).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webusers.npl.uiuc.edu/~a-nathan/pob/BESRWhitePaper.pdf|title=The BESR (Ball Exit Speed Ratio)|accessdate=31 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029095447/http://webusers.npl.uiuc.edu/~a-nathan/pob/BESRWhitePaper.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2008}}</ref> Intermediate Little League bats must meet Junior League specifications.\n\n===Base running===\nWhen the pitcher is ready to pitch, a baserunner may not leave the bag until the pitch reaches the batter in Minor League and standard Little League. In the upper levels, including Intermediate Little League, the runner can leave the bag at any time while the ball is in play.\n\nIf a fielder is waiting at the base with the ball, an advancing runner must attempt to avoid contact.  A runner may not slide head-first except when retreating to a previously held base.\n\nIn the upper levels, runners must still make an attempt to avoid contact if possible, and may not maliciously initiate contact with a fielder.\n\n===Batting===\nThe upper limit of the [[strike zone]] extends to the batter's armpits.<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/Newsletters/Fairball_Newsletters/2009/fbmay09/THESTRIKEZONE.htm THE STRIKE ZONE: Location, Location, Location] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614000727/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/Newsletters/Fairball_Newsletters/2009/fbmay09/THESTRIKEZONE.htm |date=2009-06-14 }}, Little League\u00a9 ''Online''</ref>\n\nIn Tee-ball, Minor League, and Little League (if '[[uncaught third strike]]' rule is waived by the local league), the batter is out after the [[Strikeout|third strike]] regardless of whether the pitched ball is held by the catcher.  In Little League (both standard and Intermediate), Junior, Senior, and Big League, a batter may attempt to advance to first base on a dropped third strike if first base is unoccupied with less than two outs or if first base is unoccupied or occupied with two outs.\n\nIf the batter is hit by a pitch, the batter gets walked automatically. However, if the batter does not make an attempt to get out of the way of the pitched ball, the home-plate umpire may continue the at-bat.\n\n===Substitution===\nPlayers who have been substituted for may return to the game under certain conditions, though a player who is removed as pitcher may not return to pitch.\n\n===Pitchers===\n[[Pitcher]]s in all divisions are limited to a specific pitch count per game and a mandatory rest period between outings. These vary with age. The rest period also depends on the number of pitches thrown.<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/rules/pitch_count_resource_page.htm Pitch Count Resource Page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726152644/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/rules/pitch_count_resource_page.htm |date=2008-07-26 }}, Little League\u00a9 ''Online''</ref>\n\nIf the pitcher hits too many batters with the ball, or intentionally hits the batter, he is ejected from the pitching spot.\n\n;Intentional base on balls\nHistorically, a pitcher could [[intentional base on balls|intentionally walk]] a batter by simply announcing his intent to do so and not have to actually throw any pitches. Beginning in 2008, the pitcher had to actually pitch the required four balls (which were counted against the pitch count). In 2017, the Major and Minor levels of Little League Baseball aligned with a new rule of Major League Baseball and allowed the pitcher to intentionally walk a batter simply by declaration. The intentional walk adds four to the pitcher's pitch count.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.llumpires.com/2017-little-league-rule-regulation-changes/\n|title=2017 Little League Rule and Regulation Changes\n|publisher=LLUmpires.com\n|date=2017-03-13\n|accessdate=2017-05-17\n}}</ref> This change rescinded a former rule in which the team at bat could decline the award of first base and force the pitcher to pitch, to further increase the pitch count against the pitcher.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://theseason.gc.com/basbeall-new-little-league-intentional-walk-rules-change-strategy\n|title=New Little League Intentional Walk Rules Change Strategy\n|publisher=GameChanger\n|date=2017-02-22\n|accessdate=2017-05-17\n}}</ref>\n\n===Local options===\nLocal leagues have a certain amount of flexibility.  For example, a league may opt to use the \"continuous batting order\" rule (4.04), under which each player on the team's roster bats, even when not in the defensive lineup.  Leagues may also waive the \"[[mercy rule#Baseball and softball|ten-run rule]]\" (4.10(e)) which ends the game if one team is ahead by ten or more [[Run (baseball)|runs]] after four innings.<ref>[http://www.scn.org/ncll/rules.html Rules of Little League], Seattle Community Network (scn.org)</ref><ref>[http://www.wmbumpires.com/rules/llinterps.pdf Little League Rules and Interpretations of Note] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080923202801/http://www.wmbumpires.com/rules/llinterps.pdf |date=2008-09-23 }}, Western Maine Board of Baseball Umpires (wmbumpires.com)</ref>\n\n==MLB Players==\n:''For a list of current and former Major League Baseball players who played in the Little League World Series, see footnote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.littleleague.org/Little_League_Big_Legacy/Little_League_World_Series/From_Little_League_reg__to_the_Majors.htm |title=Current and Former Major Leaguers who have Played in the Little League Baseball World Series |publisher=Little League |accessdate=2017-03-30}}</ref>\n{{expand list|date=March 2017}}\nThe following is an '''incomplete''' list of current and former [[Major League Baseball]] players who played Little League Baseball.\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Roberto Alomar]] *\n* [[Wilson \u00c1lvarez]] *\n* [[Jeff Bagwell]]\n* [[Jason Bay]] *\n* [[Derek Bell (baseball)|Derek Bell]] *\n* [[Cody Bellinger]] *\n* [[Larvell Blanks]] *\n* [[Wade Boggs]]\n* [[George Brett]]\n* [[Steve Carlton]]\n* [[Gary Carter]]\n* [[Bobby Cox]]\n* [[Rollie Fingers]]\n* [[Todd Frazier]] *\n* [[Tom Glavine]]\n* [[Randal Grichuk]] *\n* [[Ken Hubbs]] *\n* [[Joey Jay]]\n* [[Randy Johnson]]\n* [[Carney Lansford]] *\n* [[Lance Lynn]] *\n* [[Greg Maddux]]\n* [[Jason Marquis]] *\n* [[Lloyd McClendon]] *\n* [[Jim Palmer]]\n* [[Wes Parker]]\n* [[Mike Piazza]]\n* [[Boog Powell]] *\n* [[Jurickson Profar]] *\n* [[Colby Rasmus]] *\n* [[Cal Ripken, Jr.]]\n* [[Iv\u00e1n Rodr\u00edguez]]\n* [[Nolan Ryan]]\n* [[Mike Schmidt]]\n* [[Tom Seaver]]\n* [[Jonathan Schoop]] *\n* [[Gary Sheffield]] *\n* [[Don Sutton]]\n* [[Ruben Tejada]] *\n* [[Frank Thomas (designated hitter)|Frank Thomas]]\n* [[Joe Torre]]\n* [[Mike Trout]]\n* [[Jason Varitek]] *\n* [[Dave Veres]] *\n* [[Dan Wilson (baseball)|Dan Wilson]] *\n* [[Rick Wise]] *\n* [[Carl Yastrzemski]]\n* [[Robin Yount]]\n{{div col end}}\n:<nowiki>*</nowiki> ''participated in Little League World Series''\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Little League World Series champions by division]]\n*[[List of Little League Softball World Series champions by division]]\n* [[Amateur baseball in the United States]]\n* [[Major League Baseball]]\n* [[List of organized baseball leagues]]\n* {{section link|Baseball awards|World}}\n* {{slink|Baseball awards|U.S. youth baseball}}\n* [[Baseball clothing and equipment]]\n\n==References==\n\n===General===\n* Van Auken, Lance and Robin. ''Play Ball: The Story of Little League Baseball'', Pennsylvania State University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|0-271-02118-7}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.littleleague.org/}}\n* [http://www.littleleague.org/museum/ Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050207004043/http://www.littleleague.org/series/history/historicalresults.htm Little League World Series Champions]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070417133707/http://littleleague.cl/ Little League Foundation Chile]\n\n<!--spacing, please do not remove-->\n\n{{Little League}}\n\n[[Category:Little League World Series|-]]\n[[Category:Children's sport]]\n[[Category:Youth sport in the United States]]\n[[Category:Softball organizations]]\n[[Category:Youth baseball]]\n[[Category:Youth baseball in the United States]]\n[[Category:Baseball governing bodies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Baseball in Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Lycoming County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 1939]]\n[[Category:1939 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Patriotic and national organizations chartered by the United States Congress]]\n[[Category:Little League| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|See: [[Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball|Intermediate, Junior, and Senior League Baseball]]}}\n{{Infobox sports league\n| title          = Little League Baseball, Incorporated\n| upcoming_season= 2019 Little League World Series\n| logo           = Little League Baseball - Logo.jpg\n| sport          = [[Baseball]], [[softball]]\n| founded        = {{Baseball year|1939}} in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania|Williamsport]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[United States of America|U.S.]]\n| fame           = Largest organized youth sports organization in the world\n| motto          = Courage, Character, and Loyalty\n| inaugural      = 1939\n| competitors    = 2,600,000\n| teams          = over 180,000\n| Leagues        = approximately 7,500\n| qualification  = [[2019 Little League World Series qualification|Little League International Tournament]]\n| website        = {{URL|http://www.Littleleague.org/}}\n| ceo            = Stephen D. Keener\n| director       = David Houseknecht, [[Chief Financial Officer|CFO]]\n| coo            = Patrick Wilson\n| tv             = [[ESPN]], [[ESPN2]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]; [[Madison Square Garden Network]] (MSG), [[New England Sports Network]] (NESN)\n| founder        = [[Carl E. Stotz]], George Bebble, Bert Bebble\n}}\n'''Little League Baseball and Softball''' (officially, '''Little League Baseball Inc'''<ref name= corp/>) is a [[501(c)(3)]] [[nonprofit organization]]<ref name= irseos>\"[https://apps.irs.gov/app/eos/displayAll.do?dispatchMethod=displayAllInfo&Id=4564989&ein=231688231&country=US&deductibility=all&dispatchMethod=searchAll&isDescending=false&city=&ein1=23-1688231&postDateFrom=&exemptTypeCode=al&submitName=Search&sortColumn=orgName&totalResults=1&names=&resultsPerPage=25&indexOfFirstRow=0&postDateTo=&state=All+States Little League Baseball Inc, EIN: 23-1688231]\". ''Tax Exempt Organization Search''. [[Internal Revenue Service]]. Retrieved August 22, 2018.</ref><ref>\"[https://www.guidestar.org/FinDocuments/2017/231/688/2017-231688231-0efaa9bf-9.pdf Form 990: Return of Organization Exempt from Income Tax]\". ''Little League Baseball Incorporated''. [[Guidestar]]. September 30, 2017.</ref> based in [[South Williamsport, Pennsylvania]], [[United States of America|United States]], that organizes local youth [[baseball]] and [[softball]] [[sports league|leagues]] throughout the United States and the rest of the world.\n\nFounded by [[Carl Stotz]], George Bebble, and Bert Bebble in 1939 as a three-team league in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]], and formally incorporated on October 10, 1950,<ref name= corp>\"[https://www.corporations.pa.gov/search/CorpSearch Little League Baseball Inc]\". ''Corporation Search''. Pennsylvania Department of State. Retrieved August 22, 2018.</ref> Little League Baseball encourages local volunteers to organize and operate Little League programs that are annually chartered through Little League International. Each league can structure itself to best serve the children in the area in which the league operates. Several specific divisions of Little League baseball and softball are available to children ages 4 to 16. The organization holds a [[congressional charter]] under [[Title 36 of the United States Code]].<ref>Section 130501(a) of [[Title 36 of the United States Code]] provides that Little League Baseball, Incorporated is a [https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/36/130501 \"federally chartered corporation\"].</ref>\n\nThe organization's administrative office is located in South Williamsport, Pennsylvania. The first Little League Baseball World Series was played in Williamsport in 1947. The Little League International Complex hosts the annual [[Little League Baseball World Series]] at [[Howard J. Lamade Stadium]] and [[Little League Volunteer Stadium]], and is also the site of the [[Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum]], which provides a history of Little League Baseball and Softball through interactive exhibits for children. Many [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) players played in Little League.\n\n==History==\nCarl Stotz, a resident of Williamsport, Pennsylvania, founded Little League Baseball in 1939. He began experimenting with his idea in the summer of 1938 when he gathered Carl's nephews, Jimmy and Major Gehron and their neighborhood friends. They tried different field dimensions over the course of the summer and played several informal games. The following summer they felt that they were ready to establish what later became Little League Baseball. The first league in Williamsport had just three teams, each sponsored by a different business. The first teams, Jumbo Pretzel, Lycoming Dairy, and Lundy Lumber, were managed by Carl Stotz, and brothers George and Bert Bebble. The men, joined by their wives and another couple, formed the first-ever Little League Board of Directors.<ref name=\"llbhistory\">{{cite web |url = http://www.littleleague.org/about/history.asp |title = History of Little League |accessdate = 2007-06-26 |publisher = Little League |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070514082459/http://www.littleleague.org/about/history.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-05-14}}</ref>\n\nThe first League game took place on June 6, 1939. Lundy Lumber defeated Lycoming Dairy, 23-8. Lycoming Dairy came back to claim the league [[championship]]. They, the first-half-season champions, defeated Lundy Lumber, the second-half champs, in a best-of-three season-ending [[playoff format|series]]. The following year a second league was formed in Williamsport, and from there Little League Baseball grew to become an international organization of nearly 200,000 teams in every U.S. state and over 80 countries around the world.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\nFrom 1951 through 1973, Little League was for boys only. In 1974, Little League [[Regulation of sport|rules]] were revised to allow participation by girls in the baseball program following the result of a lawsuit filed by the [[National Organization for Women]] on behalf of [[Maria Pepe]].<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/About_Our_Organization/historyandmission/chronology.htm Little League: History and Mission: Chronology] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224170800/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/About_Our_Organization/historyandmission/chronology.htm |date=2009-02-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"mario_pepe_bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/05_2004/04mariapepeopening.htm|title=Little League World Series Opening Ceremony to Mark 30th Anniversary of Decision Allowing Girls to Play|date=August 9, 2004|accessdate=2009-09-13|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607002311/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/05_2004/04mariapepeopening.htm|archivedate=June 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1953, Robert Francis Morrison filed an official charter with Little League Baseball, Incorporated to admit the Cannon Street Y.M.C.A., as its first all-black team.  The league consisted of four teams, sponsored by prominent black businesses in [[Charleston, South Carolina]].<ref name=\"Sport in American History\">{{Cite news|url=https://ussporthistory.com/2014/09/01/baseball-dreams-deferred-the-story-of-the-cannon-street-y-m-c-a-all-stars-part-two/|title=Baseball Dreams Deferred: The Story of the Cannon Street Y.M.C.A. All Stars (Part Two)|date=2014-09-02|work=Sport in American History|access-date=2018-08-20|language=en-US}}</ref> In 1955, when Morrison entered the Cannon Street All-Stars into the city tournament, white leagues reacted by drafting a resolution requesting a whites-only tournament.  All 55 white teams eventually withdrew from the city and state tournament.  The Cannon Street All-Stars became the 1955 South Caroline state champions by forfeit.  However, they were informed by Little League president, Peter J. McGovern, that they would not be permitted to represent the state at the regional championships in Williamsport, GA. Little League executives invited the Cannon Street All-Stars to attend the tournament as guests to view the World Series that they were not permitted to play in.<ref name=\"Sport in American History\"/>\n\nAccording to the Little League Baseball and Softball participation statistics following the 2008 season, there were nearly 2.6 million players in Little League Baseball worldwide, including both boys and girls, including 400,000 registered in softball (also including both boys and girls). For tournament purposes, Little League Baseball is divided into 16 geographic regions; eight National and eight international. Each summer, Little League operates seven World Series tournaments at various locations throughout the U.S. (Little League softball and Junior, Senior, and Big League baseball and softball).\n\n===Timeline===\n\n====Early years====\n'''1939''': Little League is established by [[Carl E. Stotz]]. The first season is played in a lot close to [[Bowman Field (stadium)|Bowman Field]]. Lycoming Dairy is the first season champion.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1946''': Little League has expanded to 12 leagues, all in Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1947''': The first league outside of Pennsylvania is founded in [[Hammonton, New Jersey]]. Maynard League of Williamsport defeats a team from [[Lock Haven, Pennsylvania]] to win the first Little League World Series. [[Allen Yearick]] is the first Little League graduate to play professional baseball when he is signed by the [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1948''': Little League has grown to include 94 leagues. Lock Haven returns to the Little League World Series and defeats a league from [[St. Petersburg, Florida]]. The first corporate sponsor, [[U.S. Rubber]], is announced,<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>  who donate [[Pro-Keds]] shoes to teams at the Little League World Series.<ref name=\"geist\">{{cite book | last = Geist | first = Bill | title = Little League Confidential: One Coach's Completely Unauthorized Tale of Survival | year = 1999 | edition = 1st | publisher = Dell | location = New York | isbn = 0-440-50877-0 }}</ref>\n\n'''1949''': Little League is featured in the ''[[Saturday Evening Post]]'' and on [[newsreel]]s. Carl Stotz gets hundreds of requests for information on how to form leagues at the local level from all over the United States. Little League incorporates in New York.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1950 or 1951''' (sources contradict) Kathryn 'Kay' Johnston -Massar became the first girl to play Little League baseball. Her mother cut her braids and she dressed like a boy. Not knowing what to call herself, she adopted the nickname \"Tubby\" because of her love of Little Lulu comic books, and joined the Kings Dairy Little League team in Corning, N.Y., posing as a boy.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/blog/big_league_stew/post/Katie-Reyes-becomes-first-girl-gamewinner-at-Lit?urn=mlb-185105 Katie Reyes becomes first girl gamewinner at Little League WS - Big League Stew - MLB Blog - Yahoo! Sports]. Sports.yahoo.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref> After earning her way onto the team and being assigned first base, she told her coach she was a girl, but he said \"That's O.K., you're a darned good player.\" Kay, aka 'Tubby' (which all her teammates continued to call her even after they knew the truth), played first base for the season, but was forced to quit after just one season because a new rule, known as the ''Tubby Rule, was created. It'' declared, \"Rule III (f) Girls are not eligible under any circumstances.\"; that rule was in force until 1974.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/08/20/sports/baseball-one-more-pitch-for-first-girl-in-little-league.html | work=The New York Times | first=Neil | last=Amdur | title=BASEBALL; One More Pitch for First Girl in Little League | date=2001-08-20}}</ref>\n\n'''1951''': Leagues are formed in [[British Columbia]], Canada and near the Panama Canal making them the first leagues outside the United States.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1953''': The Little League World Series is televised for the first time. [[Jim McKay]] provides the play by play for [[CBS]]. [[Howard Cosell]] provides play by play for [[Citadel Media|ABC Radio]]. [[Joey Jay]] of [[Middletown, Connecticut]] and the [[Milwaukee Braves]] is the first Little League graduate to play in the [[Major League Baseball|Major Leagues]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1954''': [[Boog Powell]], who later played for the [[Baltimore Orioles]] plays in the Little League World Series for [[Lakeland, Florida]]. [[Ken Hubbs]], who later played for the [[Chicago Cubs]], plays in the Little League World Series for [[Colton, California]]. Little League has expanded to more than 3,300 leagues.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> Jim Barberi who later played for the Los Angeles Dodgers and in a Major League World Series was also a member of the [[Schenectady, New York]] team who won the 1954 Series.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''1955''': There is a Little League organization in each of the 48 U.S. States. [[George W. Bush]] begins playing Little League as a [[catcher]] for the Cubs of the Central Little League in [[Midland, Texas]]. He is the first Little League graduate to be elected President of the United States.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>  The all-black Cannon Street YMCA All-Stars in [[Charleston, South Carolina]] created an uproar that every other Little League organization in South Carolina refused to play Cannon Street.  Little League sent an ultimatum that the team be able to play, which the other leagues refused, where the other 61 organizations returned their charters and formed their own league in response.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1995/10/30/8098327/little-leagues-civil-war-in-55-a-black-allstar-team-was-sidelined-by-a-racial-boycott-in-south-carolina|title=LITTLE LEAGUE'S CIVIL WAR IN '55 A BLACK ALL-STAR TEAM WAS SIDELINED BY A RACIAL BOYCOTT IN SOUTH CAROLINA|work=Vault|access-date=2018-08-20|language=en}}</ref>  No team from the state had made the tournament until 2015.\n\n'''1956''': Carl Stotz severs his ties with Little League Baseball in a dispute over the direction and control of Little League. Stotz believed the league was becoming over-commercialized by Little League president, Peter J. McGovern.<ref name=stotzbio>{{cite web|title=Carl Edwin Stotz|url=http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Stotz__Carl.html|publisher=Pennsylvania Center for the Book|accessdate=17 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218234504/http://pabook.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Stotz__Carl.html|archivedate=18 February 2015}}</ref> Stotz remains active in youth baseball with the \"Original League\" in Williamsport.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> Little League records its first on-field death in [[Garland, Texas]] as 12-year-old Richard \"Rick\" Oden is hit in the head by a pitch thrown by Jerry Armstrong.  The city park location of the incident is renamed \"Rick Oden Field.\"  As batting helmets are yet to be developed, Garland teams finish the season wearing youth football helmets over their baseball caps when batting.  Later that year, Fred Shapiro throws a perfect game in the Little League World Series.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n====International era====\n[[File:RiceAmbMrsKellyLittleLeagueCut 600.jpg|thumb|right|250px|U.S. Secretary of State [[Condoleezza Rice]] poses with Little Leaguers from Chile in [[Santiago, Chile|Santiago]]]]\n'''1957''': Angel Macias throws a perfect game and [[Monterrey, Mexico|Monterrey]], Mexico, becomes the first team from outside the United States to win the Little League World Series. (Portrayed in 2010 film \"[[The Perfect Game]]\".)<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1959''': The Little League World Series moves from Williamsport to the newly built Little League Headquarters in [[South Williamsport, Pennsylvania|South Williamsport]]. The protective baseball [[batting helmet|helmet]] is developed by Dr. Creighton J. Hale.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1960''': A team from [[West Berlin]], [[West Germany]], is the first team from Europe to play in the Little League World Series. The series is broadcast live for the first time on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]. Little League has grown to 27,400 teams in more than 5,500 leagues.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1961''': [[Brian Sipe]], future [[quarterback]] for the [[Cleveland Browns]], plays for the series champions from [[El Cajon, California]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1962''': [[Jackie Robinson]] attends the Little League World Series. President [[John F. Kennedy]] proclaims National Little League Week.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1967''': A team from West Tokyo, Japan, is the first team from Asia to win the Little League World Series.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1969''': Taiwan begins a dominant era that would see them win 17 Little League World Series titles.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1971''': The aluminum baseball bat is first used. It was partly developed by Little League Baseball. [[Lloyd McClendon]] of [[Gary, Indiana|Gary]], Indiana, dominates the Little League World Series, hitting five [[home run]]s in five at-bats. He later played in the Major Leagues and become the first Little League graduate to manage an MLB club with the [[Pittsburgh Pirates]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1973''': [[Ed Vosberg]] plays in the Little League World Series for [[Tucson, Arizona|Tucson]], Arizona. He later played in the [[College World Series]] for the [[University of Arizona]] in 1980 and the [[World Series]] in 1997 for the [[Florida Marlins]]. Vosberg is the first person to have played in all three world series.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1974''': Girls are formally permitted to play in the Little League Baseball program as result of lawsuit brought on behalf of Frances Pescatore<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.si.com/vault/1974/04/22/614696/now-georgy-porgy-runs-away/ | work=CNN | title=Now Georgy-porgy Runs Away | date=1974-04-22 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019035438/http://www.si.com/vault/1974/04/22/614696/now-georgy-porgy-runs-away | archivedate=2015-10-19 }}</ref> and [[Jenny Fulle]],<ref>{{cite news|title=No More Discrimination / Little League Relents, Votes To Allow Girls To Play Ball|newspaper=The Marin Independent Journal|date=June 13, 1974|page=14}}</ref> and a Little League Softball program for both boys and girls is created. Bunny Taylor becomes the first girl to pitch a no-hitter.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/page2/s/list/moments/uswomen.html ESPN.com - Page2 - Greatest U.S. women's sports moments]. Espn.go.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n\n'''1975''': In a controversial decision, all foreign teams are banned from the Little League World Series. International play is restored the following year.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1980''': A team from [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], Florida, representing Belmont Heights Little League, is led by two future major leaguers [[Derek Bell (baseball)|Derek Bell]] and [[Gary Sheffield]]. Bell returns the following year and Belmont Heights again loses in the finals to a team from Taiwan.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1982''': The Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum opens. Cody Webster leads a team from [[Kirkland, Washington]], in an upset victory of a powerful team from Taiwan. It was Taiwan's first loss in 31 games.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> This game was later featured on ESPN's [[30 for 30]] series ''Little Big Men.''\n\n'''1984''': [[Seoul]], South Korea, wins the first title for a South Korean team. They defeat a team from [[Altamonte Springs, Florida]], led by future [[Boston Red Sox]] catcher, [[Jason Varitek]].<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1984:''': Victoria Roche, a 12-year-old from Belgium, becomes the first girl to play in the Little League World Series.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/espnw/title-ix/timeline/ Timeline - espnW] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605065812/http://espn.go.com/espnw/title-ix/timeline/ |date=2012-06-05 }}. Espn.go.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n\n'''1988''': [[Tom Seaver]] is the first former Little Leaguer to be enshrined in the Peter J. McGovern Museum Hall of Excellence.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1989''': Poland becomes the first former [[Warsaw Pact]] nation to receive a Little League charter. [[Trumbull, Connecticut]], led by future [[National Hockey League|NHL]] star [[Chris Drury]], wins the Little League World Series.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1991''': Future NL All Star [[Jason Marquis]] pitches the Staten Island South Shore Little League team to third place in the Little League World Series over Canada, throwing a [[no-hitter]].<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=1907492 \"World Series may pit former Little League stars against each other,\" ''[[ESPN]]'', 10/25/04, accessed 6/6/07]</ref>\n\n'''1992''': Carl Stotz, the founder of Little League, dies. Lights are installed at Lamade Stadium allowing for the first night games to be played. The series is expanded from single elimination to round-robin format. [[Long Beach, California|Long Beach]], California, managed by former Major Leaguer [[Jeff Burroughs]] and led by his son, future Major Leaguer [[Sean Burroughs]], is named series champion after [[Zamboanga City]], Philippines, is forced to forfeit for playing with ineligible players.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1993''': Long Beach repeats as champions, defeating Coquivacoa Little League of [[Maracaibo, Venezuela|Maracaibo]], Venezuela. It is the first U.S. team to successfully defend its title.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1997''': [[ESPN2]] broadcasts regional play for the first time. Taiwan's baseball association withdraws from Little League Baseball (they would rejoin in 2003) over newly established rules on zoning.  Bradenton, Florida, and Pottsville, Pennsylvania, play at Lamade Stadium before the largest crowd ever to attend a non-championship game. The crowd was estimated at over 35,000 fans.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''1999''': [[Burkina-Faso]] becomes the 100th nation with a Little League organization. Hirkata Little League of [[Osaka]], Japan, becomes the first Japanese team to win a title since 1976.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/>\n\n'''2000''': An expansion project begins at Little League International. Volunteer Stadium is built. This allows the <ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> pool of participants to be doubled from 8 to 16 the following year.\n\n'''2001''': The LLWS expands from 8 to 16 teams, with the following changes to regional lineups (post-2000 regions in '''bold'''):\n* US regions:{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n** The East Region splits into the '''New England''' and '''Mid-Atlantic''' Regions.\n** The Central Region splits into the '''Great Lakes''' and '''Midwest''' Regions.\n** The South Region splits into the '''Southeast''' and '''Southwest''' Regions.\n** The '''West''' Region spins off the '''Northwest''' Region.\n* International regions:{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n** '''Canada''' remains intact as a region.\n** The '''Latin America''' Region spins off new regions for the '''Caribbean''' and '''Mexico'''.\n** The Far East Region splits into the '''Asia''' and '''Pacific''' Regions.\n** The '''Europe''' Region spins off the '''TransAtlantic'''<!--This is LL's official spelling.--> Region.\n*** These two regions were geographically identical, differing in the required composition of playing rosters. Transatlantic teams were required to consist of a majority of players who were nationals of the US, Canada, or Japan. Europe teams could have no more than three nationals of those countries.\n\nIn other news, Volunteer Stadium is opened. [[George W. Bush]] becomes the first U.S. president to visit the Little League World Series.<ref name=\"llbhistory\"/> Led by phenom [[Danny Almonte]], pitching the first perfect game since 1957, the Rolando Paulino All Stars ([[The Bronx|Bronx]], New York) finish third in the series. The team's entire postseason, however, is wiped from the books when it is found that Almonte was 14 years old.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2002''':  [[Austin Dillon]] plays for Southwest Forsyth (County) Little League in [[Clemmons, North Carolina]].  The grandson of [[Richard Childress]], he would win [[NASCAR]] championships in the [[Camping World Truck Series]] in [[2011 NASCAR Camping World Truck Series|2011]] and [[Nationwide Series]] in [[2013 NASCAR Nationwide Series|2013]], and made his [[Sprint Cup Series|Sprint Cup]] debut in [[2014 NASCAR Sprint Cup Series|2014]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2004''': Effective with the 2004 LLWS, the Europe Region is renamed '''EMEA''', for Europe, Middle East, Africa.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2007''': Little League expands into Australia for the first time. Effective with the 2007 LLWS, the Asia and Pacific regions are merged to form the '''Asia-Pacific''' Region, with '''Japan''' being split into its own region.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2007''': Little League expands into [[Kyrgyzstan]] for the first time{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2008''': Effective with this year's LLWS, the Transatlantic and EMEA regions are reorganized into the '''Europe''' and '''Middle East and Africa (MEA)''' regions. The previous nationality restrictions for players from these regions are abolished. Hawai'i wins the 2008 Little League World Series beating Mexico in the Final.\n\n'''2008''': Little League International relocates the Southeast Region Headquarters From Gulfport, Florida, to Warner Robins, Ga. Little League International completes renovation of its administration building in South Williamsport, Pa.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2010''': The World Series tournament is reorganized, eliminating pool play and adopting double-elimination until the bracket winners are determined. Little League announces plans to add a pilot division in baseball for ages 12\u201313 to help baseball Little Leaguers make the transition to regulation-size fields in Junior League Baseball. Bartlett, Illinois, becomes biggest little league.<ref name=pilotdivision>{{cite news |work=Sports Illustrated |date=January 11, 2010 |title=Little League plans new division |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/baseball/mlb/01/11/little.league.division.ap/index.html?xid=si_mlb |accessdate=2010-01-14 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n'''2011''':  The World Series officially eliminates the two four-team brackets and puts all eight teams in the United States bracket and all eight teams in the International bracket, with a [[SEC Baseball Tournament]] style flipped bracket on the loser's bracket to prevent rematches, but does not require the loser to defeat the winner's bracket team twice in either Saturday championship game where the winner advances to the Sunday final.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2012''':\n: The '''Middle East and Africa''' Region produces the first team from the African continent in the Little League World Series: youngsters from Lugazi Little League of [[Uganda]].\n: On August 29, Little League announces a major reorganization of the international brackets, effective with the 2013 LLWS:<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2012/May-Aug/RegionsRealignedfor2013WS.htm |title=Regions Realigned for 2013: Australia to Play in Little League Baseball World Series |publisher=Little League Baseball |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=September 17, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120923225531/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2012/May-Aug/RegionsRealignedfor2013WS.htm |archivedate=September 23, 2012 }}</ref>\n:* '''Australia''' spun off from the Asia\u2013Pacific Region and receive its own berth in the LLWS. This reflects Australia's rise to become the fourth-largest country, and largest outside North America, in Little League participation.\n:* The Middle East and Africa Region is disbanded.\n:* Middle Eastern countries, except for Israel and Turkey (which had been in the Europe Region\u2014see below), are placed in the '''Asia\u2013Pacific Region'''.\n:* African countries will be placed in the former Europe Region, which is renamed the '''Europe and Africa Region'''. Israel and Turkey, members of [[Confederation of European Baseball|the European zone]] of the [[International Baseball Federation]],  remains in the renamed region.\n: The Intermediate (50/70) Division, which had operated on a pilot basis since the 2011 season, was announced as an official Little League division, the first new division since 1999. The division, which launched fully in the 2013 season, has the same age limits as standard Little League but extends the pitching rubber to 50 feet from home plate and features bases 70 feet apart. The field is also larger than in standard Little League, and the rules are closer to those of standard baseball.{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n'''2013''':\n: Davie Jane Gilmour became the first woman to lead the board of directors for Little League.<ref>[http://psdispatch.com/news/baseball/607398/Gilmour-is-Little-Leagues-first-female-board-chair Gilmour is Little League\u2019s first female board chair - The Sunday Dispatch] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216061154/http://psdispatch.com/news/baseball/607398/Gilmour-is-Little-Leagues-first-female-board-chair |date=December 16, 2013 }}. Psdispatch.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-23.</ref>\n: The first [[Intermediate League World Series|Intermediate Little League World Series]] is held, in [[Livermore, California]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://intermediateworldseries.org/2013-intermediate-world-series/|title=2013 Intermediate World Series|date=August 5, 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''2014''':\n: On August 15, 2014, [[Mo'ne Davis]] was the first girl in [[Little League World Series]] history to pitch a winning game for the Taney Dragons and earned the win,<ref name=NYT>{{cite news |last1=Rhoden |first1=William C. |title=A Mound Becomes a Summit: Mo'ne Davis Dominates at Little League World Series. South Korea won the world series against Jackie Robinson West. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/16/sports/baseball/mone-davis-dominates-at-little-league-world-series.html?_r=0 |accessdate=August 17, 2014 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 15, 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RtrCi94i?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/08/16/sports/baseball/mone-davis-dominates-at-little-league-world-series.html?_r=1 |archivedate=August 17, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> and she was also the first girl to pitch a shutout in Little League postseason history.<ref name=NPR1>{{cite news |last1=Jacobs |first1=Emma |title=Mo'ne Davis Throws Like A Girl\u2014At 70 MPH |url=https://www.npr.org/2014/08/16/340912807/mone-davis-throws-like-a-girl-at-70-mph |accessdate=August 17, 2014 |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=August 16, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817183257/http://www.npr.org/2014/08/16/340912807/mone-davis-throws-like-a-girl-at-70-mph |archivedate=August 17, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite news |last1=Berg |first1=Ted |title=13-year-old sensation Mo'Ne Davis throws two-hit shutout at Little League World Series |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/08/mone-davis-dominant-llws-pitcher |accessdate=August 17, 2014 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=August 15, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140816001858/http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/08/mone-davis-dominant-llws-pitcher |archivedate=August 16, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Davis also became the first Little Leaguer to be on the cover of ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' (which she was for the issue dated August 25, 2014.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2014/08/19/mone-davis-sports-illustrated-cover/|title=Little League Star Mo'ne Davis Hits Sports Illustrated's Cover|first=Sam|last=Laird|publisher=|accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> ESPN's coverage of the semifinals game in which Davis played August 20 brought a 3.4 overnight rating, which is an all-time high for Little League on ESPN.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/mone-davis-pitches-record-ratings-726839 | work=The Hollywood Reporter | title=Mo'ne Davis Pitches Record Ratings for Little League World Series | date=2014-08-21}}</ref>\n\n: Jackie Robinson West became the first all-African-American Little League team to win the U.S. championship, but it was later vacated due to violations of the 1997 region regulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/sports/chicago-wins-us-title-little-league-world-series/ng74h/|title=Chicago wins U.S. title in Little League World Series|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3162110/baseball-african-americans-chicago/|title=All Black Team Could Be First to Win Little League World Series|author=Sean Gregory|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/chicago/story/_/id/12308988/little-league-strips-chicago-team-us-championship-suspends-coach|title=Little League strips Chicago team of U.S. championship, suspends coach \u2013 ESPN Chicago|work=ESPN.com}}</ref>\n\n'''2018''':\nLittle League changes its age rules, moving the birthday deadline from May 1 back to August 31. This allows 13-year-olds to play Majors level this year against 11-year-olds but those 11-year-olds born between May and August will be unable to play next year.<ref>https://www.littleleague.org/news/update-implementation-little-league-baseball-age-determination-date/</ref>\n\n==Regions==\n[[File:2013 Little League Baseball Map.png|thumb|right|600px|Map of Little League regions]]\n{{For|the regions in the other age divisions|Intermediate, Junior, and Senior League Baseball#Regions}}\nThe national regions represented in the annual Little League Baseball World Series are:\n* {{Color box|#BFEFFF}} New England\n* {{Color box|#800080}} Great Lakes\n* {{Color box|#0000CD}} Mid-Atlantic\n* {{Color box|#1C86EE}} Midwest\n* {{Color box|#87CEFA}} Southeast\n* {{Color box|#DDA0DD}} Southwest\n* {{Color box|#000080}} Northwest (including Alaska)\n* {{Color box|#00F5FF}} West (including Hawaii)\nThe international regions are:\n* {{Color box|#FF0000}} Canada<!--spacing, please do not remove-->\n* {{Color box|#FFFF00}} Mexico\n* {{Color box|#00FF00}} Asia-Pacific\n* {{Color box|#008000}} Japan\n* {{Color box|#EE7AE9}} Europe and Africa\n* {{Color box|#FF0080}} Australia\n* {{Color box|#EEC900}} Latin America\n* {{Color box|#EE9A00}} Caribbean\n\n[[Image:Little League World Series and Lamade Stadium.JPG|thumb|550px|center|A Little League World Series game in Howard J. Lamade Stadium in South Williamsport.]]\n\n==Little League World Series==\n[[File:Little League World Series Game 1 crop.jpg|thumb|right|275px|A game of the 2007 Little League World Series]]\nThe best-known event on the Little League Baseball and Softball calendar is the annual [[Little League World Series|Little League Baseball World Series]], which is held every August in [[South Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]. Local and regional tournaments leading up to the World Series are held in the U.S. insular areas of [[Puerto Rico]], the [[U.S. Virgin Islands]], and the [[Northern Mariana Islands]], and throughout the world. In 2003, for example, there were tournaments in Canada, Latin America ([[Mexico]], [[Aruba]], [[Cura\u00e7ao]], [[Panama]], [[Peru]], and [[Venezuela]]), Europe (Germany and Poland), and Asia (Japan, [[Philippines]], [[South Korea]], [[Taiwan]]).\n\n===Little, Junior, Senior, and Big League baseball & softball World Series===\nThe Little League Baseball World Series is just one of nine World Series conducted by Little League International every year, each one held in a different location.\n* [[Little League World Series]] (baseball)\n* [[Intermediate League World Series|Intermediate Little League World Series]] (baseball)\n* [[Junior League World Series]] (baseball)\n* [[Senior League World Series]] (baseball)\n* [[Big League World Series]] (baseball) ''(discontinued after 2016)''\n* [[Little League Softball World Series|Girls Little League Softball World Series]] (or the Major Division)<ref name=GirlsSoftballWldSeries>[http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/sbworldseries.htm Softball World Series] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819120316/http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/sbworldseries.htm |date=2017-08-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref>\n* [[Junior League World Series (softball)|Girls Junior League Softball World Series]]\n* Girls Senior League Softball World Series<ref name=GirlsSoftballWldSeries/>\n* Girls Big League Softball World Series<ref name=GirlsSoftballWldSeries/> \n''(discontinued after 2019)''\n1950 1951 1952 1953 1954 1955 1956 1957 1958 1959 1960 1961 1962 1963 1964 1965 1966 1967 1968 1969 1970 1971 1972 1973 1974 1975 1976 1977 1978 1979 1980 1981 1982 1983\n1984 1985 1986 1987 1988 1989 1990 1991 1992 1993 1994 1995 1996 1997 1998 1999 2000\n2001 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009 2010 2011 2012 2013 2014 2015 2016 2017 2018 2019 \n* Boys Little League Softball World Series<ref>\n* 1950 *1951 * 1952 * 1953 * 1954 *1955 *1956 * 1957 *1958 *1959 *1960 *1961 *1962 * * 1963 *1964 * 1965 * 1966 * 1967 *1968 *1969 * 1970 *1971 *1972 *1973 *1974 *1975 * * 1976 *1977 * 1978 * 1979 * 1980 *1981 *1982 * 1983 *1984 *1985 *1986 *1987 *1988 * * 1989 *1990 * 1991 * 1992 * 1993 *1994 *1995 * 1996 *1997 *1998 *1999 *2000 *2001\n* 2002 *2003 * 2004 * 2005 * 2006 *2007 *2008 * 2009 *