o|Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum#Hall of Excellence|Baseball awards#Little League Baseball}}\n* Good Sport of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/goodsportaward.htm Good Sport of the Year Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106143045/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/goodsportaward.htm |date=2009-11-06 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Challenger Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/challengeraward.htm Challenger Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519200918/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/challengeraward.htm |date=2009-05-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* ASAP (A Safety Awareness Program) Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Assets/forms_pubs/asap/AwardsOverview_2010.pdf 2010 ASAP Awards Overview and Past Winners]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} (national and regional). Little League. Retrieved 2009-12-06.</ref>\n* Bill Shea Distinguished Little League Graduate Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/distinguishedaward.htm Bill Shea Distinguished Little League Graduate Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826161238/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/distinguishedaward.htm |date=2009-08-26 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Mom of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/momaward.htm Mom of the Year Award.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106134426/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/momaward.htm |date=2009-11-06 }} Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* George and Barbara Bush Little League Parents of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/parentsaward.htm George and Barbara Bush Little League Parents of the Year Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106143054/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/parentsaward.htm |date=2009-11-06 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Volunteer of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/volunteeraward.htm Volunteer of the Year Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724083210/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/volunteeraward.htm |date=2009-07-24 }} Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Howard and Gail Paster Little League Urban Initiative Volunteer of the Year Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/uivolunteeraward.htm Howard and Gail Paster Little League Urban Initiative Volunteer of the Year Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091128082939/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/awards/uivolunteeraward.htm |date=2009-11-28 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2009-11-25.</ref>\n* Howard Hartman Little League Friendship Award<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2008stories/2008HowardHartmanAwardWinner.htm \"Howard Hartman Award at Little League World Series\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607010523/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2008stories/2008HowardHartmanAwardWinner.htm |date=2011-06-07 }}, Little League Communications Department, August 15, 2008. Little League. Retrieved 2009-12-06.</ref>\n\n==Baseball divisions==\nLittle League Baseball has several baseball divisions for boys, girls  based on age.<ref name=LL_divisions>{{cite web | url = http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/baseball/llbb.htm | title = Little League Baseball (or the Major Division) | author = Little League Baseball, Incorporated | accessdate = May 12, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100508041321/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/baseball/llbb.htm | archive-date = 2010-05-08 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n===Summary chart of major divisions in Little League Baseball===\n{{see also|List of Little League World Series champions by division}}\nThe major divisions of Little League Baseball have their own World Series format as follows:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" | Division\n!scope=\"col\" | Location\n!scope=\"col\" | First Held\n!scope=\"col\" | Age of players\n!scope=\"col\" | Series\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Little League Baseball\n| [[South Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]\n| 1947\n| 9\u201312 years old\n| [[Little League World Series]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Little League Baseball#Little League Intermediate (50/70) Division|Intermediate League Baseball]]\n| [[Livermore, California]]\n| 2013\n| 11\u201313 years old\n| [[Intermediate League World Series]]<!--This is the official name of this level's LLWS.-->\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Junior League Baseball]]\n| [[Taylor, Michigan]]\n| 1981\n| 13\u201314 years old\n| [[Junior League World Series]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball|Senior League Baseball]]\n|[[Easley, South Carolina|Easley]], [[South Carolina]]\n| 1961\n| 14\u201316 years old\n| [[Senior League World Series]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | [[Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball|Big League Baseball]]\n| [[Easley, South Carolina]]\n| 1968\n| 16\u201318 years old\n| [[Big League World Series]]<BR>''(discontinued after 2016)''\n|}\n\n===Tee-ball===\n<!--Blatant copyright infringement removed; please do not re-add-->\n{{see also|Tee-ball}}\nTee-ball is for boys and girls ages 4\u20135, with local leagues given the option to allow 6\u20137-year-olds to play. In Tee-ball, players hit the ball off of a tee located atop [[home plate]]; live pitching is not allowed. The purpose of the division is to teach young children the basic fundamentals of hitting and fielding.<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Minor leagues===\n<!--Blatant copyright infringement removed; please do not re-add-->\nThe Minor League Baseball division is generally for children ages 7\u201311, with local leagues given the option to allow 6-year-old children to try out. Local leagues are permitted to further divide the Minor League division based on player age and/or experience, and often consist of coach-pitch (i.e., the batter's coach lightly pitching the ball) or machine-pitch at lower levels, with defensive players pitching at higher levels.<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===9\u201310 year olds===\n\"The 9\u201310 Year Old Baseball Division for boys and girls was established as a tournament program in 1994. It gives children of this age the opportunity to experience tournament competition, up to state level. Players on these teams can be chosen from among Major Division and/or Minor Division teams. The diamond used is a 60-foot diamond and the pitching distance is 46 feet.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Little League (or the Major Division)===\n{{see also|Little League World Series}}\n\"The Little League Baseball Division (sometimes known as the Major Division) is for boys and girls ages 9\u201312. A local league may choose to limit its Major Division to 10-, 11-, and 12-year-olds, or 11\u201312-year-olds. The diamond used is a 60-foot diamond and the pitching distance is 46 feet. The local league has an option to choose a Tournament Team (or 'All Stars') of 11\u201312-year-olds from within this division, and the team may enter the International Tournament. The culmination of the International Tournament is the Little League Baseball World Series, featuring teams from around the globe. All expenses for the teams advancing to the World Series (travel, meals, and housing) are paid by Little League Baseball.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Little League Intermediate (50/70) Division===\n{{see also|Intermediate, Junior, and Senior League Baseball}}\nIn 2012, Little League announced plans to add a new division of play for the 2013 season, the Little League Intermediate Division.  This Division is played on a field with a {{convert|50|ft|m|adj=on}} pitching distance and {{convert|70|ft|m|adj=on}} base paths.  It is open to players ages 11\u201313, but may be limited to ages 11\u201312 or 12\u201313 by a local league.  Players in this division are able to lead off and steal. The rules follow rules similar to those of the Junior, Senior, and Big League Divisions of play.\n\nLittle League holds a World Series in this level of play, officially called the [[Intermediate League World Series|Intermediate Little League World Series]], in [[Livermore, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2012/Sep-Dec/LittleLeagueAnnouncesNameofNewBaseballDivisionIntermediate5070.htm|title=Little League Announces Intermediate (50/70) Division|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130415063307/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2012/Sep-Dec/LittleLeagueAnnouncesNameofNewBaseballDivisionIntermediate5070.htm|archivedate=2013-04-15}}</ref>\n\n===Junior League===\n{{main|Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball}}\n\"The Junior League Baseball Division is a program for boys and girls ages 13\u201314, using a conventional {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=on}} diamond with a pitching distance of {{convert|60|ft|6|in|m}}. (A modified diamond is available during the regular season.) The local league has an option to choose a Tournament Team (or \"All Stars\") of 13\u201314-year-olds from within this division (and/or from within the Senior League Division), and the team may enter the International Tournament. The culmination of the International Tournament is the Junior League Baseball World Series, featuring teams from around the globe. All expenses for the teams advancing to the World Series (travel, meals, and housing) are paid by Little League Baseball.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Senior League===\n{{main|Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball}}\n\"The Senior League Baseball Division is for boys and girls 14\u201316 years old, using a conventional {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=on}} diamond with a pitching distance of {{convert|60|ft|6|in|m}}. The local league has an option to choose a Tournament Team (or \"All Stars\") of 14- to 16-year-olds from within this division (and/or from within the Junior League or Big League divisions), and the team may enter the International Tournament. The culmination of the International Tournament is the Senior League Baseball World Series, featuring teams from around the globe. All expenses for the teams advancing to the World Series (travel, meals, and housing) are paid by Little League Baseball.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n===Big League===\n{{main|Junior, Senior & Big League Baseball}}\n:''Note: The Big League division was discontinued after the [[2016 Big League World Series]].\n\"The Big League Baseball Division is for boys and girls ages 16\u201318, using a conventional {{convert|90|ft|m|adj=on}} diamond with a pitching distance of {{convert|60|ft|6|in|m}}. The local league has an option to choose a Tournament Team (or \"All Stars\") of 16\u201318-year-olds from within this division (and/or from within the Senior League Division), and the team may enter the International Tournament. The culmination of the International Tournament is the Big League Baseball World Series, featuring teams from around the globe. All expenses for the teams advancing to the World Series (travel, meals, and housing) are paid by Little League Baseball.\"<ref name=LL_divisions/>\n\n==Challenger program==\nLittle League introduced the Challenger Division in 1989 to provide opportunities for children with physical and intellectual challenges to participate in the Little League program.  The Challenger Division utilizes a \"buddy system\" in which Little Leaguers assist Challenger participants in the areas of batting, running and fielding.  Challenger Division games are typically non-competitive in nature.<ref name=LLC_division>\n {{cite web | url = http://www.LittleLeagueChallenger.org | title = Little League Challenger Division| author=Little League Baseball, Incorporated | date = | accessdate=March 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Little League Challenger Division===\nIntroduced in 1989, the Little League Challenger Division is for participants ages 4\u201318.  Games are played on a 46/60 field and are non-competitive.\n\n===Senior League Challenger Division===\nApproved at the 2014 Little League International Congress the Senior League Challenger Division launched in 2015.  This division is for participants ages 15 and above (no maximum age).  Games are played on a 60/90 field and are non-competitive.  Leagues may request permission to play games on a smaller field as well.\n\n===Participation===\nAs of 2018, nearly 1,000 Little Leagues in 10 countries around the world offered the Challenger Program providing an opportunity for more than 31,000 individuals with physical or intellectual challenges to participate in the Little League program.\n\n==Softball divisions==\nLittle League Baseball has several softball divisions for girls and boys, based on age.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" | Division\n!scope=\"col\" | Location\n!scope=\"col\" | First Held\n!scope=\"col\" | Age of players\n!scope=\"col\" | Series\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Little League Softball\n| [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| 1974\n| 9\u201312 years old<ref name=\"littleleague.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/softballdivisions.htm?FullPageView=True|title=Softball \u2013 Divisions of Play|accessdate=31 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160913204706/http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/softballdivisions.htm?FullPageView=True|archive-date=2016-09-13|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| Little League World Series (softball)\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Junior League Softball\n| [[Kirkland, Washington]]\n| 1999\n| 12\u201314 years old<ref name=\"littleleague.org\"/>\n| [[Junior League World Series (softball)]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Senior League Softball\n| [[Sussex County, Delaware]]\n| 1976\n| 13\u201316 years old<ref name=\"littleleague.org\"/>\n| Senior League World Series (softball)\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" | Big League Softball\n| [[Kalamazoo, Michigan]]\n| 1982\n|14\u201318 years old<ref name=\"littleleague.org\"/>\n| Big League World Series (softball)\n|}\n\n===Boys softball===\n:''See footnote''<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys.htm Boys Softball Divisions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819120356/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-boys.htm |date=2017-08-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref>\n* Tee Ball Softball for Boys\n* Minor League Softball for Boys\n* Little League Softball (or the Major Division) for Boys\n* Senior League Softball for Boys\n* Big League Softball for Boys\n\n===Girls softball===\n:''See footnotes''<ref name=GirlsSoftballWldSeries/><ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-girls.htm Divisions of Play: Girls Softball Divisions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171219011711/http://www.littleleague.org/learn/about/divisions/softball-girls.htm |date=2017-12-19 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref><ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/softballdivisions.htm Softball Division: Girls Softball Divisions] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171221172949/http://www.littleleague.org/media/softball/softballdivisions.htm |date=2017-12-21 }}. Little League. Retrieved 2011-08-24.</ref>\n* Girls Tee Ball Softball\n* Girls Minor League Softball\n* Girls Little League Softball (or the Major Division)\n{{see also|Little League Softball World Series}}\n* Girls Junior League Softball\n{{see also|Junior League World Series (softball)}}\n* Girls Senior League Softball\n* Girls Big League Softball\n\n==Rules==\nThe playing rules for the baseball divisions essentially follow the \"[[baseball rules#Codes|Official Baseball Rules]]\" (as defined by and used by [[Major League Baseball]] and published at [http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/official_info/official_rules/foreword.jsp Official Baseball Rules at MLB.com]), especially with respect to the upper divisions (Junior, Senior, and Big League).  Some major exceptions are outlined in the following sections, and these apply to Little League (Minor and Major, ages 7\u201312) except as otherwise noted.\n\n===Rulebooks and fees===\nUnlike Major League Baseball and most other sports such as [[American football|football]], [[soccer]], and [[basketball]], the official rules of Little League Baseball are available to the general public only by online subscription ($20)<ref name=ll_rulebooks>\n {{cite web | url = http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2010/Jan-Apr/2010RedesignedRuleBooksNowAvailable.htm | title = 2010 Redesigned Rule Books Now Available | author = Little League Baseball, Incorporated | date = Jan 5, 2010 | accessdate = May 12, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100511073540/http://www.littleleague.org/media/newsarchive/2010/Jan-Apr/2010RedesignedRuleBooksNowAvailable.htm | archivedate = May 11, 2010 }}</ref> or as a printed edition ($7<ref name=ll_rulebooks/> plus $3 for \"shipping and handling\" within the US via [[United Parcel Service|UPS]]<ref name=ll_rulebook_internet>\n {{cite web | url = http://www.littleleaguestore.net/135.html | title = Little League Store - 2010 Baseball Rule Book | author = Little League Baseball, Incorporated | year = 2010 | accessdate = May 12, 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100611213200/http://littleleaguestore.net/135.html | archivedate = June 11, 2010 }}</ref>). In Canada, rulebook orders requested through LittleLeague.ca are routed to the US website at the same prices, except that \"shipping and handling\" to Canada via UPS is US$15.51, for a total of US$22.51 for a single printed copy.<ref name=ll_rulebook_internet/>\n\nRulebooks are not available in sporting goods stores or other stores and must be ordered directly from Little League Baseball, Incorporated or one of its \"Regional Centers\".<ref name=ll_rulebooks/><ref name=Gub>{{cite news | first = Ted | last = Gub | title =  Who's on First? Who Wants to Know, and Why?| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/07/28/AR2007072801205.html | work = Washington Post | page = D1 | date = July 29, 2007 | accessdate = 2008-07-03 | quote = }}</ref>  One paper copy is provided to each team that has sent in an \"Application for Charter and Insurance\",<ref name=ll_rulebooks/> although previously two copies were provided.<ref name=Gub/>\n\nLittle League has been criticized for requiring payment to view its rules.<ref name=Gub/> However, the organization counters by claiming it has been exposed to lawsuits in the past in cases involving organizations not officially affiliated with Little League but which nonetheless use its rules.<ref name=Gub/>\n\n===Length of game===\nA regulation game is 6 [[inning]]s.  If the game is called prior to the completion of six innings, it is considered an official game if four innings have been completed (three and a half, if the home team leads); otherwise, if at least one inning has been completed, it is a suspended game.\n\nIn Intermediate Little League, as well as the Junior, Senior, and Big League levels (ages 13\u201318), a game is seven innings and is official if five innings have been completed.\n\n===Mandatory-play rule===\nIn all divisions except Senior and Big League, every player on the team roster must have at least one plate appearance and play six consecutive outs on defense in each game.  The penalty for a manager violating the rule is a two-game suspension.  This rule is waived if the game is completed prior to the usual duration of the game (six innings in Little League and below, seven innings in Intermediate Little League and Junior League).  This rule is modified during tournament play.  During tournament play, teams that have 13 or more players dressed at the field for a game are mandated to have one (1) \"At Bat\" during the game per player with no defensive requirement.  Teams that have 12 or fewer players dressed at the field for a tournament game require each player to receive one (1) \"At Bat\" plus six consecutive outs played in the field on defense.\n\n===Playing field===\nThe size of the field is dependent on the division of play.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mysite.verizon.net/rutherford.ll/rules2.htm|title=Pay Bill, See Offers, Check Email with My Verizon Fios|website=mysite.verizon.net|access-date=2009-01-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090531162505/http://mysite.verizon.net/rutherford.ll/rules2.htm|archive-date=2009-05-31|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n'''Tee-ball'''\n:The distance between the bases is generally {{convert|50|ft|m|2}}.\n\n'''Minor League and Little League'''\n:The distance between the bases is {{convert|60|ft|m|2}} and the distance from the [[pitcher's mound]] to home plate is {{convert|46|ft|m|2}}.  Outfield fences must be at least {{convert|165|ft|m}} from home plate, but are usually {{convert|200|ft|m|-1}} or more (the fields at the Williamsport complex have fences 225 feet away).  The bases and pitching rubber are also slightly smaller than in standard baseball.{{Citation needed|reason=The field specification section of littleleague.org does not mention difference in base size|date=April 2014}} Also, unlike fields at almost all levels of competitive baseball for teenagers and adults, the distance between home plate and the outfield fence is constant throughout fair territory.\n\n'''Intermediate Little League'''\n:The distance between the bases is {{convert|70|ft|m|2}} and the distance from the pitcher's mound to home plate is {{convert|50|ft|m|2}}.  The recommended distance between home plate and the outfield fence ranges from {{convert|200|to(-)|275|ft|m|round=5}}; unlike regular Little League, the distances can vary within fair territory.  As in regular Little League, the bases and pitching rubber are also slightly smaller than in standard baseball.\n\n'''Junior League, Senior League, and Big League'''\n:The distance between the bases is {{convert|90|ft|m|2}}, the same as for regulation [[Major League Baseball]] fields. The distance between the pitcher's mound to home plate is {{convert|60.5|ft|m|2}}, also identical to that of MLB. The minimum outfield distance in the upper divisions is {{convert|300|ft|m}} (compare with MLB's official but not strictly enforced minimum of {{convert|325|ft|m|disp=sqbr}} at the foul lines), while the maximum for Big League is {{convert|425|ft|m}}.  (Base paths of {{convert|80|ft|m|2|disp=sqbr}} are optional for Junior League regular season play.)\n\n===Equipment===\n[[File:Little league baseball bunt.JPG|thumb|right|200px|A Little Leaguer executing a bunt]]\n[[Baseball bat|Bats]] (all levels) may be made from wood or other materials (such as [[aluminum]]) and must be approved for use in Little League Baseball.  For the Majors Division and below, the maximum bat length is thirty-three (33) inches (838&nbsp;mm) and barrel diameter may not exceed {{convert|2+1/4|in|mm}}.  Beginning in 2009 all Little League bats must be labeled with a Bat Performance Factor (BPF) of 1.15 or lower.\n\nBats for the Junior League level may have a maximum length of thirty-four (34) inches (864&nbsp;mm) and a maximum barrel diameter of {{convert|2+5/8|in|mm}}.  Bats for the Big and Senior League levels may have a maximum length of thirty-six (36) inches (914&nbsp;mm) and a maximum barrel diameter of {{convert|2+5/8|in|mm}}.  Non-wood Big and Senior League bats must meet the Batted Ball Coefficient of Restitution (BBCOR) testing standards that are currently used in the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] and [[National Federation of State High School Associations|NFHS]] (high school).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://webusers.npl.uiuc.edu/~a-nathan/pob/BESRWhitePaper.pdf|title=The BESR (Ball Exit Speed Ratio)|accessdate=31 August 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029095447/http://webusers.npl.uiuc.edu/~a-nathan/pob/BESRWhitePaper.pdf|archivedate=29 October 2008}}</ref> Intermediate Little League bats must meet Junior League specifications.\n\n===Base running===\nWhen the pitcher is ready to pitch, a baserunner may not leave the bag until the pitch reaches the batter in Minor League and standard Little League. In the upper levels, including Intermediate Little League, the runner can leave the bag at any time while the ball is in play.\n\nIf a fielder is waiting at the base with the ball, an advancing runner must attempt to avoid contact.  A runner may not slide head-first except when retreating to a previously held base.\n\nIn the upper levels, runners must still make an attempt to avoid contact if possible, and may not maliciously initiate contact with a fielder.\n\n===Batting===\nThe upper limit of the [[strike zone]] extends to the batter's armpits.<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/Newsletters/Fairball_Newsletters/2009/fbmay09/THESTRIKEZONE.htm THE STRIKE ZONE: Location, Location, Location] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090614000727/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/Newsletters/Fairball_Newsletters/2009/fbmay09/THESTRIKEZONE.htm |date=2009-06-14 }}, Little League\u00a9 ''Online''</ref>\n\nIn Tee-ball, Minor League, and Little League (if '[[uncaught third strike]]' rule is waived by the local league), the batter is out after the [[Strikeout|third strike]] regardless of whether the pitched ball is held by the catcher.  In Little League (both standard and Intermediate), Junior, Senior, and Big League, a batter may attempt to advance to first base on a dropped third strike if first base is unoccupied with less than two outs or if first base is unoccupied or occupied with two outs.\n\nIf the batter is hit by a pitch, the batter gets walked automatically. However, if the batter does not make an attempt to get out of the way of the pitched ball, the home-plate umpire may continue the at-bat.\n\n===Substitution===\nPlayers who have been substituted for may return to the game under certain conditions, though a player who is removed as pitcher may not return to pitch.\n\n===Pitchers===\n[[Pitcher]]s in all divisions are limited to a specific pitch count per game and a mandatory rest period between outings. These vary with age. The rest period also depends on the number of pitches thrown.<ref>[http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/rules/pitch_count_resource_page.htm Pitch Count Resource Page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726152644/http://www.littleleague.org/Learn_More/rules/pitch_count_resource_page.htm |date=2008-07-26 }}, Little League\u00a9 ''Online''</ref>\n\nIf the pitcher hits too many batters with the ball, or intentionally hits the batter, he is ejected from the pitching spot.\n\n;Intentional base on balls\nHistorically, a pitcher could [[intentional base on balls|intentionally walk]] a batter by simply announcing his intent to do so and not have to actually throw any pitches. Beginning in 2008, the pitcher had to actually pitch the required four balls (which were counted against the pitch count). In 2017, the Major and Minor levels of Little League Baseball aligned with a new rule of Major League Baseball and allowed the pitcher to intentionally walk a batter simply by declaration. The intentional walk adds four to the pitcher's pitch count.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://www.llumpires.com/2017-little-league-rule-regulation-changes/\n|title=2017 Little League Rule and Regulation Changes\n|publisher=LLUmpires.com\n|date=2017-03-13\n|accessdate=2017-05-17\n}}</ref> This change rescinded a former rule in which the team at bat could decline the award of first base and force the pitcher to pitch, to further increase the pitch count against the pitcher.<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=http://theseason.gc.com/basbeall-new-little-league-intentional-walk-rules-change-strategy\n|title=New Little League Intentional Walk Rules Change Strategy\n|publisher=GameChanger\n|date=2017-02-22\n|accessdate=2017-05-17\n}}</ref>\n\n===Local options===\nLocal leagues have a certain amount of flexibility.  For example, a league may opt to use the \"continuous batting order\" rule (4.04), under which each player on the team's roster bats, even when not in the defensive lineup.  Leagues may also waive the \"[[mercy rule#Baseball and softball|ten-run rule]]\" (4.10(e)) which ends the game if one team is ahead by ten or more [[Run (baseball)|runs]] after four innings.<ref>[http://www.scn.org/ncll/rules.html Rules of Little League], Seattle Community Network (scn.org)</ref><ref>[http://www.wmbumpires.com/rules/llinterps.pdf Little League Rules and Interpretations of Note] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080923202801/http://www.wmbumpires.com/rules/llinterps.pdf |date=2008-09-23 }}, Western Maine Board of Baseball Umpires (wmbumpires.com)</ref>\n\n==MLB Players==\n:''For a list of current and former Major League Baseball players who played in the Little League World Series, see footnote.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.littleleague.org/Little_League_Big_Legacy/Little_League_World_Series/From_Little_League_reg__to_the_Majors.htm |title=Current and Former Major Leaguers who have Played in the Little League Baseball World Series |publisher=Little League |accessdate=2017-03-30}}</ref>\n{{expand list|date=March 2017}}\nThe following is an '''incomplete''' list of current and former [[Major League Baseball]] players who played Little League Baseball.\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Roberto Alomar]] *\n* [[Wilson \u00c1lvarez]] *\n* [[Jeff Bagwell]]\n* [[Jason Bay]] *\n* [[Derek Bell (baseball)|Derek Bell]] *\n* [[Cody Bellinger]] *\n* [[Larvell Blanks]] *\n* [[Wade Boggs]]\n* [[George Brett]]\n* [[Steve Carlton]]\n* [[Gary Carter]]\n* [[Bobby Cox]]\n* [[Rollie Fingers]]\n* [[Todd Frazier]] *\n* [[Tom Glavine]]\n* [[Randal Grichuk]] *\n* [[Ken Hubbs]] *\n* [[Joey Jay]]\n* [[Randy Johnson]]\n* [[Carney Lansford]] *\n* [[Lance Lynn]] *\n* [[Greg Maddux]]\n* [[Jason Marquis]] *\n* [[Lloyd McClendon]] *\n* [[Jim Palmer]]\n* [[Wes Parker]]\n* [[Mike Piazza]]\n* [[Boog Powell]] *\n* [[Jurickson Profar]] *\n* [[Colby Rasmus]] *\n* [[Cal Ripken, Jr.]]\n* [[Iv\u00e1n Rodr\u00edguez]]\n* [[Nolan Ryan]]\n* [[Mike Schmidt]]\n* [[Tom Seaver]]\n* [[Jonathan Schoop]] *\n* [[Gary Sheffield]] *\n* [[Don Sutton]]\n* [[Ruben Tejada]] *\n* [[Frank Thomas (designated hitter)|Frank Thomas]]\n* [[Joe Torre]]\n* [[Mike Trout]]\n* [[Jason Varitek]] *\n* [[Dave Veres]] *\n* [[Dan Wilson (baseball)|Dan Wilson]] *\n* [[Rick Wise]] *\n* [[Carl Yastrzemski]]\n* [[Robin Yount]]\n{{div col end}}\n:<nowiki>*</nowiki> ''participated in Little League World Series''\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Little League World Series champions by division]]\n*[[List of Little League Softball World Series champions by division]]\n* [[Amateur baseball in the United States]]\n* [[Major League Baseball]]\n* [[List of organized baseball leagues]]\n* {{section link|Baseball awards|World}}\n* {{slink|Baseball awards|U.S. youth baseball}}\n* [[Baseball clothing and equipment]]\n\n==References==\n\n===General===\n* Van Auken, Lance and Robin. ''Play Ball: The Story of Little League Baseball'', Pennsylvania State University Press, 2001. {{ISBN|0-271-02118-7}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.littleleague.org/}}\n* [http://www.littleleague.org/museum/ Peter J. McGovern Little League Museum]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050207004043/http://www.littleleague.org/series/history/historicalresults.htm Little League World Series Champions]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070417133707/http://littleleague.cl/ Little League Foundation Chile]\n\n<!--spacing, please do not remove-->\n\n{{Little League}}\n\n[[Category:Little League World Series|-]]\n[[Category:Children's sport]]\n[[Category:Youth sport in the United States]]\n[[Category:Softball organizations]]\n[[Category:Youth baseball]]\n[[Category:Youth baseball in the United States]]\n[[Category:Baseball governing bodies in the United States]]\n[[Category:Baseball in Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Lycoming County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Sports leagues established in 1939]]\n[[Category:1939 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Patriotic and national organizations chartered by the United States Congress]]\n[[Category:Little League| ]]\n", "name_user": "I dream of horses", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 23-8 \u2192 23\u20138", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_League_Baseball"}
