 lutes]]\n[[Category:Mongolian traditional music]]\n", "name_user": "I dream of horses", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morin_khuur"}
{"title_page": "Moccasin Bluff Site", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Moccasin Bluff Site\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Moccasin Bluff Site.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= Red Bud Trail near [[Buchanan, Michigan]]<ref>The NRIS lists the Moccasin Bluff Site as \"Address Restricted.\" However, the State of Michigan has erected a historical marker at the site ([http://www.michmarkers.com/startup.asp?startpage=L1437.htm Moccasin Bluff] from MichMarkers.org).</ref>\n  | coordinates = {{coord|41|51|20|N|86|22|0|W|region:US-MI_type:railwaystation|display=inline,title}}\n  | locmapin = Michigan#USA\n  | architect OR builder = \n  | architecture = \n  | added = April 13, 1977\n  | area = {{convert|5|acre}}\n  | refnum = 77000710<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Moccasin Bluff Site''' (also designated '''20BE8''') is an [[archaeological site]] located along Red Bud Trail and the [[St. Joseph River (Lake Michigan)|St. Joseph River]] north of [[Buchanan, Michigan]]. It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1977<ref name=\"nris\"/>, and has been classified as a multi-component [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] site with the major component dating to the [[Late Woodland]]/[[Upper Mississippian]] period.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe terrace between Moccasin Bluff and the [[St. Joseph River (Michigan)|St. Joseph River]] was home to temporary camps as early as 6300 B.C.  Around A.D 500, inhabitants here traded with other groups of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] from [[Illinois]] and [[Indiana]]. By A.D. 1100-1400, more permanent villages were established here, and the residents farmed the local lands.<ref name = \"michmark\">{{citation | title = Traveling Through Time: A Guide to Michigan's Historical Markers  |editor = Laura R. Ashlee | publisher = University of Michigan Press | year = 2005 | isbn = 9780472030668 | page = 42 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Xd-mh9r0zEkC&pg=PA42#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 1820s, European settlers moved into the area to log and farm the land. The US government then adopted a policy of moving the local [[Potawatomi]] out of the area and further west. This bluff is said to be named for Cogomoccasin, leader of one of the nearby displaced Potawatomi villages. <ref name = \"michmark\"/>\n\nIn 1948, the site was excavated by a [[University of Michigan]] team, which found [[pottery]], [[Burial|burials]] and remnants of [[maize]] and storage pits. In 2002, [[Michigan State University]] excavated a wetland area at a lower elevation that had not been previously examined.<ref name = \"lp\"/>\n\n==Description==\nThe Moccasin Bluff Site is located on a terrace along Red Bud Trail. The terrace overlooks a wide bend in the [[St. Joseph River (Michigan)|St. Joseph River]] containing a pair of islands. The site is protected by a half-circle of hills to the north, west and south.<ref name = \"lp\">{{citation | title = Moccasin Bluff a look back at local prehistory | author = Andy Hamilton | newspaper = Niles Daily Star | date = February 23, 2007 | url = http://www.leaderpub.com/2007/02/23/moccasin-bluff-a-look-back-at-local-prehistory/}}</ref>\n\nThe site is significant in being one of the few Prehistoric sites in western [[Michigan]] that have been occupied intensively for a very long period of time.  This has resulted in a rich [[midden]] which yields a large quantity of [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]].  The deposits are not stratified, but the artifacts themselves, supported by [[Radiocarbon date|radiocarbon dates]] and comparison to other sites, are  diagnostic of several periods of Native American [[prehistory]], ranging from c. 8500 BC to the 1600s A.D. or just prior to [[Europe|European]] contact.  The [[Archaic period in the Americas|Archaic]] (c. 8500-1500 BC), [[Early Woodland Period|Early Woodland]] (c. 1500-100 BC) and [[Middle Woodland]] (c. 100BC-500 AD) are represented based on the types of artifacts recovered.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  However, the main occupation was in the [[Late Woodland period]] (c. 500-1500 AD) with evidence of [[Upper Mississippian]] (c. 1000-1500 AD) occupation and/or influence as well.\n\n== Results of 1948 Excavations ==\n\nThe excavations yielded pit features, [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]], animal bone and plant remains.<ref name=\"Bettarel\">{{cite book |last1=Bettarel |first1=Robert Louis and Hale G. Smith |title=The Moccasin Bluff Site and the Woodland Cultures of Southwestern Michigan |date=1973 |publisher=University of Michigan Museum of Anthropology, Anthropological Papers No. 49 |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan}}</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\n\nThere were no trace of [[Dwelling|dwellings]] found at the site.  Nor were there post molds that might have indicated the presence of [[Building|structures]].  The researchers concluded that the lack of structural features may be due to the fact that the main part of the site was destroyed during the construction of the Red Bud Trail Highway.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\nFour feature types were identified; [[Storage pit (archaeology)|storage pits]] (62), [[Fire pit|fire pits]] (17), [[Hearth|hearths]] (19) and smudge pits (2).  Three [[Burial|burials]] were located, of which only one was fully excavated.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\nThe fire pits may have functioned as [[Earth oven|earth ovens]] for the roasting of the [[Nymphaea odorata|white water lily]] [[tuber]].<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  No trace of the tubers were found at the site, but in similar pits at the [[Griesmer Site|Griesmer site]] in northwest [[Indiana]] the carbonized remains of [[Nymphaea odorata|white water lily]] tuber were identified;<ref name=\"Faulkner\">{{cite journal |last1=Faulkner |first1=Charles H. |title=The Late Prehistoric Occupation of Northwestern Indiana: A Study of the Upper Mississippi Cultures of the Kankakee Valley |journal=Prehistory Research Series |date=1972 |volume=V |issue=1 |pages=1-222 |publisher=Indiana Historical Society |location=Indianapolis, Indiana}}</ref> and at the [[Schwerdt Site]] on the [[Kalamazoo River]] in [[Michigan]], the carbonized tubers of a similar water-lily species,  [[American Lotus]], were found in deep roasting pits.<ref name=\"McAllister\">{{cite thesis |last1=McAllister |first1=Paul W. |title=The Schwerdt Site (20AE127) Ceramics: A Berrien Phase Ceramic Assemblage in Allegan County, Michigan |degree = Masters  |date=1980 |publisher=Western Michigan University |location=Kalamazoo |page=23 |url=https://scholarworks.wmich.edu/masters_theses/1886/ |ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nBoth smudge pits contained the carbonized remains of [[maize]].  The contents were analyzed and it was determined to be Eastern Complex [[maize]].  Based on previous ethnographic observation, the researchers concluded the features were used as a smudge to cure hides.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n=== Animal Bone ===\n\nThe main species present at Moccasin Bluff were [[deer]], [[sturgeon]], [[elk]] and [[beaver]].  These bones were not modified into tools like the bone tools described in the Artifacts section below, and may be considered food remains.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n=== Plant Remains ===\n\n[[File:Charred_maize_cobs_from_smudge_pit.jpeg|thumb|right|Charred 8-rowed maize cobs from one of the smudge pits]]\n\nSpecimens of [[wood]] [[charcoal]] from the [[Fire pit|fire pits]] were analyzed and found to be primarily [[oak]], [[hickory]] and [[maple]], reflecting the makeup of the local [[deciduous forest]].  Some carbonized food remains were identified as [[acorn]], [[walnut]], [[Canadian plum]], [[Butternut tree|butternut]] and [[Hickory nut|hickory nut]].  Eastern complex [[maize]] was present in the two smudge pits.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Artifacts ===\n\nThe following types of [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]] were recovered from the site:<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n* [[Pottery]] - No whole or completely reconstructable vessels were found at the site.  Therefore the researchers looked primarily at rim sherds and distinctive body sherds to analyze the pottery. The site yielded 534 analyzable rim sherds representing at least 424 vessels.  These artifacts are discussed in more detail below.\n* [[Stone Tools]] - 1,519 [[stone tools]], tool fragments and [[Lithic flake|flakes]].<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  Also present were [[Hammerstone|hammer]] and [[anvil]] stones, [[Celt (tool)|celts]], and abraiding stones.\n* [[Bone tool|Bone tools]] - present were bone cylinders, beaming tools, [[antler]] tools, bone [[Stitching awl|awls]], [[elk]] [[scapula]] tools and [[turtle]] [[Carapace|carapaces]].  A bone rasp (musical instrument) fragment was present in the Birdsell collection, a group of artifacts from the site donated by a local collector.\n* [[Stone]] [[Pendant|Pendants]] - 2 pieces of stone were recovered with holes punched in the middle and were interpreted as [[pendant|pendants]].\n* [[Tobacco pipe|Pipes]] - 6 pipe fragments or unfinished pipe bowls made out of clay or stone.\n* [[Red Ochre]] - 7 pieces of red ochre were in the [[University of Michigan]] Museum of Anthropology collection from the site.\n\nThe non-pottery artifacts found at an archaeological site can provide useful cultural context as well as a glimpse into the domestic tasks performed at a site; ceremonial or religious activities; recreational activities; and clothing or personal adornment.\n\nSome of the most prominent and diagnostic non-pottery artifacts are presented here in more detail:<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:98%\"\n! Material !! Description !! Image !! Qty !! Function / Use !! Comments / Associations\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Small Triangular Points (aka Madison Points)\n|| [[File:Triangular_projectile_points.jpeg|125px|Triangular projectile points]]\n|| 104 (representing 44% of all chipped stone tools)\n|| Hunting/fishing/warfare\n|| Also known as \u201c[[arrowheads]]\u201d; are thought to be arrow-tips for [[Bow and arrow|bows-and-arrows.]]  The usage of the bow-and-arrow seems to have greatly increased during the [[Late Woodland]], probably as a result of increased conflict.<ref name=\"Mason\">{{cite book |last1=Mason |first1=Ronald J. |title=Great Lakes Archaeology |date=1981 |publisher=Academic Press, Incl. |location=New York, New York}}</ref><ref name=\"Lepper\">{{cite book |last1=Lepper |first1=Bradley T. |title=Ohio Archaeology |date=2005 |publisher=Orange Frazer Press |location=Wilmington, Ohio |edition=4th}}</ref>.  Since there is a large quantity of sturgeon bone at Moccasin Bluff, it is strongly probable that these tools were used in fishing activities.\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Ovate or double pointed blades/knives\n|| \n|| 3\n|| Domestic function / cutting applications\n|| Some show signs of hafting.  Typical of Upper Mississippian sites, particularly Huber and Oneota (Orr Focus)\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Bifacially flaked end scraper\n|| [[File:End_scrapers.jpeg|125px|End scrapers]]\n|| 22\n|| Domestic function / processing wood or hides\n|| Common at Oneota sites, but usually unifacially flaked rather than bifacial\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Drills\n|| [[File:T-shape_drills.jpeg|125px|T-shaped drills]]\n|| 6\n|| Domestic function / processing wood or hides\n|| 3 types are present; double pointed and expanded base, which are both common types; and T-shaped (pictured) which is usually found on Fort Ancient sites\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Thick \"steep-edge\" blades/scrapers\n|| [[File:Thick,_steep-end_blades-scrapers.jpeg|125px|Thick, steep-end blades-scrapers]]\n|| 53\n|| Domestic function / woodworking\n|| Reported from other Huber sites but not from Oneota\n|-\n| Stone\n|| Abraiding stone\n||\n|| 1\n|| Domestic function / straightening arrow shafts\n|| Considered a typical Oneota trait; also occurs in Fort Ancient culture\n|-\n| Antler\n|| Spatula pieces of antler; Chisel/gouge/scraper\n||\n|| 5\n|| Domestic function / specific use unknown\n|| Made from elk antler.  Not common on sites nearby Moccasin Bluff; has been reported on Whittlesey sites in northern Ohio\n|-\n| Bone\n|| Perforated deer bone (hole punched in the middle)\n|| [[File:Perforated_deer_bone.jpeg|95px|Perforated deer bone]]\n|| 1\n|| Possibly Personal Adornment function / pendant\n|| This type of artifact has been reported from the Fisher site and several Fort Ancient sites\n|-\n| Bone\n|| Elk scapula hoes\n|| [[File:Elk_scapula_hoe.jpeg|125px|Elk scapula hoe]]\n|| 3\n|| Domestic function / Agricultural-horticultural or general digging tool\n|| Common at Huber and Oneota sites; sometimes this tool is made with bison scapula, especially westward toward and west of the Mississippi River; they may have been used to dig out the pit features present at Moccasin Bluff.\n|-\n| Bone\n|| unmodified turtle carapace, Common Box Turtle, possibly used as bowl\n||\n|| 2\n|| Domestic function / could have been used as tobacco tray, serving bowl for food, or general food container\n|| The use of a turtle carapace as a tobacco tray has been documented among historic Central Angonkian tribes\n|-\n| Bone\n|| Bone rasp (musical instrument) fragment\n|| [[File:Bone_rasp_(musical_instrument).jpeg|125px|Bone rasp]]\n|| 1\n|| Ceremonial-Recreational function / entertainment or use at ceremony\n|| Also found at Huber, Whittlesey and Fort Ancient sites\n|-\n| Antler\n|| Grooved antler piece\n|| [[File:Grooved_antler.jpeg|70px|Grooved antler]]\n|| 1\n|| Unknown function\n|| Not common from sites in the area of Moccasin Bluff; reported from the South Park site in northern Ohio\n|-\n| Bone\n|| unmodified deer mandibles\n||\n|| \"unusually large numbers\" according to the site report\n|| Domestic function / used for scraping maize kernels off the cobs\n|| The site report does not state there is any wear on the bones to indicate their usage as a tool; but their presence in large numbers strongly implies it.  At other sites they are an indicator of the presence of maize agriculture.\n|-\n| Stone\n|| Pipe bowl fragments; stemless, vase- or bowl-shaped pipe\n||\n|| 2\n|| Ceremonial-Recreational function / pipe smoking\n|| It has been documented among historic tribes that stemless pipes were used for recreational smoking; ceremonial pipes were stemmed\n|-\n| Stone\n|| Unfinished pipe bowl fragments; stemless, block type\n||\n|| 2\n|| Ceremonial-Recreational function / pipe smoking\n|| Block style pipes are known from Whittlesey and Fort Ancient sites in Ohio\n|-\n| Clay\n|| Pipe fragments; modified tube-shaped \n||\n|| 2\n|| Ceremonial-Recreational function / pipe smoking\n|| This type is known from sites in Wisconsin\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Occupations and Associated Pottery Types ===\n\nArchaeologists often find pottery to be a very useful tool in analyzing a prehistoric culture.  It is usually very plentiful at a site and the details of manufacture and decoration are very sensitive indicators of time, space and culture.\n\n==== [[Middle Woodland]] (c. 100 BC-500 AD) ====\n \nA total of 20 vessels of Havana Ware [[pottery]] was collected in the 1948 excavations.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  The Havana Culture was thought to be a local variant of the main [[Middle Woodland]], which was dominated by the [[Adena culture|Adena]] and [[Hopewell culture|Hopewell]] cultures of the [[Mississippi River Valley|Mississippi]] and [[Ohio River Valley|Ohio River]] Valleys.<ref name=\"Mason\"/> [[Middle Woodland]] cultures are characterized by their large [[burial mounds]], some of which are still visible today; as well as their distinctive [[pottery]] forms, [[ceremonial]] practices, [[Agriculture|agricultural]] activities, and widespread [[Trade network|trade networks]].<ref name=\"Mason\"/><ref name=\"Lepper\"/>\n\n==== [[Late Woodland]] (c. 500 AD-1500 AD) / [[Upper Mississippian culture|Upper Mississipian]] (c. 1000-1500 AD)====\n\nThe [[Late Woodland]] period in the [[Great Lakes]] region was characterized by the introduction of [[maize]] [[agriculture]], which allowed for more efficient food production.  This led to [[Population growth|population increases]] which in turn led to increased competition for resources, resulting in more conflict/[[War|warfare]].  After 1000 AD, there was increased interaction and influence from the [[Mississippian culture|Mississippian]] cultures of the [[Mississippi River Valley]], resulting in the formation of [[Upper Mississippian culture|Upper Mississippian cultures]] in the [[Great Lakes area]].<ref name=\"Mason\"/>   \n\nBased on analysis of the [[Late Woodland]] / [[Upper Mississippian culture|Upper Mississippian]] [[pottery]] collected in the 1948 excavations, 2 distinct types of pottery wares were defined:  [[Late Woodland]] grit-[[Temper (pottery)|tempered]] Moccasin Bluff Ware (327 vessels) and [[Upper Mississippian]] shell-[[Temper (pottery)|tempered]] Berrien Ware (48 vessels).<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n===== Moccasin Bluff Ware (327 vessels) =====\n\n[[File:Moccasin_Bluff_Impressed_Exterior_Lip.jpg|thumb|right|Moccasin Bluff Impressed Exterior Lip rim sherd]]\n[[File:Moccasin_Bluff_Notched_Applique_Strip.jpg|thumb|right|Partially reconstructed vessel of Moccasin Bluff Notched Applique Strip]]\n[[File:Moccasin_Bluff_Plain_Modified_Lip.jpg|thumb|right|Partially reconstructed vessel of Moccasin Bluff Plain Modified Lip]]\n\nMoccasin Bluff Ware is divided into several types, some of which have variants, groups and sub-groups:<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n* Moccasin Bluff Cordmarked (97 vessels), characterized by [[Cord-marked pottery|cord marked]] surface treatment, subdivided into two varieties, Variety 1a and Variety 1b.  Variety 1b is further subdivided into 6 sub-groups.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Collared (14 vessels), characterized by collared or thickened and sometimes castellated rims, subdivided into 2 subgroups.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Modified Lip (57 vessels), characterized by distinctive rim and lip treatments, divided into 6 sub-groups.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Impressed Exterior Lip (56 vessels), characterized by distinctive rim and lip treatments, divided into 2 sub-groups.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Plain (37 vessels), characterized by a distinctive plain smoothed surface.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Plain Modified Lip (36 vessels), characterized by distinctive notches or finger impressions on the rim, combined with a plain smoothed exterior surface, subdivided into 3 sub-groups.  Similar pottery has been found at the [[Dumaw Creek Site|Dumaw Creek]], [[Summer Island Site|Summer Island]] and [[Rock Island II Site|Rock Island II]] sites.  [[Dumaw Creek Site|Dumaw Creek]] and [[Summer Island Site|Summer Island]] have been mentioned as possible [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] [[Potawatomi]] sites, and at [[Rock Island II Site|Rock Island II]], the pottery type [[Bell Site (Wn9), Wisconsin|Bell]] Type II has been demonstrated to be a [[Potawatomi]] pottery type.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/><ref name=\"Quimby\">{{cite journal |last1=Quimby |first1=George Irving |title=The Dumaw Creek Site: A Seventeenth Century Prehistoric Indian Village and Cemetery in Oceana County, Michigan |journal=Fieldiana |date=1966 |volume=56 |issue=1 |pages=1-91}}</ref><ref name=\"Brose\">{{cite book |last1=Brose |first1=David S. |title=The Archaeology of Summer Island: Changing Settlement Patterns in Northern Lake Michigan |date=1970 |publisher=University of Michigan Museum of Anthropology, Anthropological Papers No. 41 |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan}}</ref><ref name=\"Mason2\">{{cite book |last1=Mason |first1=Ronald J. |title=Rock Island: Historical Indian Archaeology in the Northern Lake Michigan Basin |date=1986 |publisher=Kent State University Press |location=Kent, Ohio |edition=MCJA Special Paper No. 6}}</ref>  '''Time Period''': Late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]].  '''Prehistoric Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].  '''Protohistoric/Historic Cultural Affiliation''': unknown, possibly [[Potawatomi]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Notched Applique Strip (20 vessels), characterized by the thickening of the rim by use of an appliqu\u00e9 strip, upon which various design motifs are applied.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  '''Time Period''': Late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]].  '''Prehistoric Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].  '''Protohistoric/Historic Cultural Affiliation''': unknown.\n* Moccasin Bluff Scalloped (10 vessels), characterized by scalloped treatment of the rim edge.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  Pottery of this type has been recovered from the [[Dumaw Creek Site|Dumaw Creek]] and [[Schwerdt Site|Schwerdt]] sites, as well as other west [[Michigan]] sites, where it is suggested it may have been made by the [[Potawatomi]].<ref name=\"Quimby\"/><ref name=\"McAllister\"/>. '''Time Period''': Late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]].    '''Prehistoric Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].  '''Protohistoric/Historic Cultural Affiliation''': unknown, possibly [[Potawatomi]].\n\n===== Berrien Ware (48 vessels) =====\n\n[[File:Berrien_Ware_pottery_-_Groups_2_and_3.jpeg|thumb|right|Berrien Ware pottery, Groups 2 and 3]]\n[[File:Berrien_Ware_-_Group_4.jpeg|thumb|right|Berrien Ware pottery, Group 4]]\n\nThe shell-[[Temper (pottery)|tempered]] Berrien Ware present at the site is divided into 5 subgroups based on shoulder, neck, surface finish and rim and lip attributes, and can be typed according to 2 previously recognized [[Upper Mississippian]] cultures:\n\n* Berrien Ware Subgroups 1, 2 and 3 - The first 3 subgroups have been equated with Huber ware, and are differentiated by shoulder and neck attributes.  Overall the Huber Ware is characterized by shell-[[Temper (pottery)|tempered]] smooth surface pottery which is either undecorated or decorated with incised or trailed lines on the shoulder area.   The Huber cultural area is centered on the [[Chicago]] area and has been recognized as closely related to the [[Oneota]] Aspect in [[Wisconsin]] and surrounding states.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>  It is dated to the late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to the Early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] or [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] period, as it has been found in association with [[Europe|European]] trade goods in some sites (c. A.D. 1400-A.D. 1650, or until [[Europe|European]] contact).<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bluhm |first1=Elaine A. and Allen Liss |title=The Anker Site, in Chicago Area Archaeology |journal=Illinois Archaeological Survey |date=1961 |volume=Bulletin No. 3 |pages=104-112}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bluhm |first1=Elaine A. and Gloria J. Fenner |title=The Oak Forest Site, in Chicago Area Archaeology |journal=Illinois Archaeological Society |date=1961 |volume=Bulletin No. 3 |pages=145-147}}</ref>.  The historic culture behind the Huber [[pottery]] is not known for certain, but the [[Miami people|Miami]] tribe were observed by early [[France|French]] explorers to occupy the area around the southern shore of [[Lake Michigan]] during the [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] to early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] Period.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  Miniature vessels have also been found within the Huber component at Moccasin Bluff.  These are common at other sites in the area and could be interpreted as \u201ctoy\u201d pots or attempts by young children to practice making pottery.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> '''Time Period''': Late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]].  '''Prehistoric Cultural Affiliation''': [[Upper Mississippian]] Huber.  '''Protohistoric/Historic Cultural Affiliation''': unknown, possibly [[Miami people|Miami]].\n* Berrien Ware Subgroups 4 and 5 - these subgroups have been equated with Fisher ware, which was first described at the Fisher Mound site in northeastern [[Illinois]] near the mouth of the [[Illinois River]].<ref name=\"Langford\">{{cite journal |last1=Langford |first1=George |title=The Fisher Mound Group, Successive Aboriginal Occupations near the Mouth of the Illinois River |journal=American Anthropologist |date=1927 |volume=29 |issue=3 |pages=153-206}}</ref>  Like Huber, Fisher is also closely related to the Oneota Aspect.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/><ref name=\"Mason\"/>  Fisher pottery is characterized by shell [[Temper (pottery)|tempering]], predominantly [[Cord-marked pottery|cordmarked]] surfaces, trailed or incised decoration and straight, excurved or flaring rims. Notched lips and rim lugs are also common.  Fisher and Huber seem to overlap spacially, as both cultures have been noted in the [[Chicago]] and northwest [[Indiana]] regions, sometimes at the same site.  The Fisher pottery at Moccasin Bluff is similar to the types Fifield Trailed and Fifield Bold, defined at the [[Fifield Site|Fifield]] site, a Fisher village site in northwestern [[Indiana]].<ref name=\"Faulkner\"/>.  Unlike the Huber Ware, Fisher has never been found associated with Protohistoric or early Historic Period sites and is therefore thought to be slightly older than Huber.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> '''Time Period:''' [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Upper Mississippian]] Fisher.\n\n===== Proposed Late Prehistoric Chronology =====\n\nThe large quantity of [[pottery]] collected at the Moccasin Bluff site, in conjunction with comparisons with other sites, enabled the authors of the site report to propose a chronological history of [[Late Woodland]] cultures in the western [[Michigan]] / northwest [[Indiana]] region.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:77%\"\n! Phase !! Date Range !! Description\n|-\n| Brems Phase\n|| c. 500-1050 A.D.\n|| Associated pottery types: Moccasin Bluff Modified Lip and Moccasin Bluff Collared\n|-\n| Moccasin Bluff Phase\n|| c. 1050-1400 A.D.\n|| Associated pottery types: Moccasin Bluff Impressed Exterior Lip, Berrien Ware Subgroups 4-5 (Fisher Ware)\n|-\n| Berrien Phase\n|| c. 1400-1650 or first European contact\n|| Associated pottery types: Berrien Ware Subgroups 1-3 (Huber Ware), Moccasin Bluff Plain Modified Lip, Moccasin Bluff Notched Applique Strip and Moccasin Bluff Scalloped.  This Phase has been dated at Moccasin Bluff by 2 [[Radiocarbon date|radiocarbon dates]] of A.D. 1590 and A.D. 1640.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\nThe Berrien Phase terminates with the end of [[Prehistory]] and the beginning of the [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] period.  The authors of the site report hypothesize that Berrien-Huber ware may be associated with the historic [[Miami tribe|Miami]] tribe; the Moccasin Bluff Scalloped with an [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]]-speaking tribe such as the [[Potawatomi]]; and the Moccasin Bluff Notched Applique Strip with [[Ohio]] tribes who may have been displaced during the [[Iroquois Wars]].<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> Based on the fact that [[Michigan]] was traditionally considered the homeland of the [[Potawatomi]], other researchers have also suggested that the Berrien Phase represents the material culture of the [[Potawatomi]] tribe.<ref name=\"Cremin\">{{cite book |last1=Cremin |first1=William M. |editor1-last=Holman |editor1-first=Margaret B., Janet G. Brashler and Kathryn E. Parker |title=The Berrien Phase of Southwest Michigan: Proto-Potawatomi?, in Investigating the Archaeological Record of the Great Lakes State: Essays in Honor of Elizabeth Baldwin Garland |date=1996 |publisher=New Issues Press |location=Kalamazoo, Michigan}}</ref>\n\nNotably, there are no [[Europe|European]] trade goods present in the Berrien Phase at Moccasin Bluff.  Therefore the site was abandoned at or just before the time of [[Europe|European]] contact.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> The same may be said for the Berrien Phase component at the nearby [[Schwerdt Site|Schwerdt]] site.<ref name=\"McAllister\"/> The reason for this may be that in the [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] period the [[Potawatomi]] were displaced from western Michigan as a result of the [[Iroquois Wars]] and moved to the west shore of [[Lake Michigan]] into [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"Cremin\"/>  The [[Rock Island II Site]] on [[Rock Island, Wisconsin|Rock Island]] in [[Green Bay (Lake Michigan)|Green Bay]], northern [[Lake Michigan]] in [[Wisconsin]] is a good example of a [[Potawatomi]] village in this early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] period.<ref name=\"Mason2\"/> As a result, the lower peninsula of Michigan became a \"no-mans land\", mostly unoccupied for several decades.<ref name=\"Cremin\"/>\n\n== Results of 2002 Excavations ==\n\nFurther excavations were conducted in 2002 to further clarify questions about the [[Subsistence economy|subsistence]] patterns and site function.<ref name=\"myth\">{{cite journal |last1=O'Gorman |first1=Jodie |title=The Myth of Moccasin Bluff: Rethinking the Potawatomi Pattern |journal=Ethnohistory |date=2007 |volume=54 |issue=3 |pages=373-406}}</ref><ref name=\"O'Gorman\">{{cite journal |last1=O'Gorman |first1=Jodie |title=Revisiting the Moccasin Bluff Site |journal=Michigan Archaeologist |date=2003 |volume=49 |issue=1-2 |pages=7-38}}</ref>  Further examples of Moccasin Bluff Ware were recovered; Moccasin Bluff Plain Modified Lip, Moccasin Bluff Impressed Exterior Lip, Moccasin Bluff Scalloped, Moccasin Bluff [[Cord-marked pottery|Cordmarked]], and Moccasin Bluff Plain.<ref name=\"O'Gorman\"/>  In addition, there were vessels recovered from the [[Middle Woodland]] and also a partially reconstructed vessel from the [[Early Woodland Period|Early Woodland]], a poorly represented time period in the 1948 excavations.<ref name=\"O'Gorman\"/>\n\nThe 2002 excavations used the [[Flotation (archaeology)|flotation]] technique to recover small plant remains, a practice that was not used in earlier times.  As a result, numerous small seeds and fruit seeds were recovered.  Of the fruits, [[pin cherry]], [[pokeberry]], [[grape]] and [[blackberry]]/[[raspberry]] were present.  Of the seeds, several indigenous starchy and oily seed were recovered, including [[goosefoot]], [[maygrass]], [[knotweed]], [[amaranth]], [[sumpweed]], and [[sunflower].  These seeds are part of the [[Eastern Agricultural Complex]], a group of cultivated or semi-cultivated plants utilized by the Prehistoric populations in addition to the better-known crops such as [[maize]], [[Bean|beans]] and [[Cucurbita|squash]]. These types of small seeds are not likely to be recovered unless [[Flotation (archaeology)|flotation]] is used, which is why they were underreported and largely unknown until [[Flotation (archaeology)|flotation]] [[Sampling (statistics)|sampling]] became widespread among [[Archaeology|archaeologists]].<ref name=\"O'Gorman\"/>\n\n== Site function and Berrien Phase settlement patterns ==\n\nThe data recovered from the Moccasin Bluff site shows many indications that the site was occupied for most or all of the year:\n\n* Maize was present at the site, implying it was planted in the spring and harvested in the fall; the presence of numerous deer mandibles implies processing of maize at the site\n* The sturgeon spawning run is in the spring, indicating spring occupation\n* Nutshell was present, indicating a fall occupation\n* Deer may be taken at any time of the year, but in the fall they are at their maximum weight and have grown thicker coats.  The early Historic Native American tribes were observed to have an annual fall deer hunt in which the deer were \"driven\" and killed in mass.\n* Numerous storage pits were present, implying food was stored over the winter\n\nBased on evidence from the excavations, combined with evidence from the early Historic Native American tribes, it was concluded that the Moccasin Bluff site represented a permanent or semi-permanent site, with other sites such as Schwerdt serving as temporary encampments to exploit seasonal resources.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fitting |first1=James E. and Charles E. Cleland |title=Late Prehistoric Settlement Patterns in the Upper Great Lakes |journal=Ethnohistory |date=1969 |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=289-302}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cleland |first1=Charles E. |title=Prehistoric Animal Ecology and Ethnozoology of the Upper Great Lakes Region |date=1966 |publisher=University of Michigan |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan |edition=Museum of Anthropology Anthropological Papers no. 29}}</ref>  There are no structures reported from Moccasin Bluff, but the researchers felt that the part of the site containing the houses was destroyed in the building of a highway through the area.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\nThe 2002 excavations found no additional evidence of [[maize]] and still no evidence of structures, and some archaeologists are re-thinking the agricultural village interpretation.  Since there is a lack of known [[Late Woodland]] or [[Upper Mississippian culture|Upper Mississippian]] [[protohistoric]] village sites elsewhere in western [[Michigan]], some researchers are suggesting that perhaps the resources available in the area simply did not support large villages and thus, small occupations and encampments were the norm until [[Europe|European]] contact times.<ref name=\"O'Gorman\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation | author1 = Robert Louis Bettarel | author2 = Hale Gilliam Smith | title = The Moccasin Bluff site and the Woodland cultures of southwestern Michigan | year =1973}}\n*{{citation | author = Jodie A. O'Gorman | title = The myth of Moccasin Bluff: rethinking the Potawatomi pattern | journal = Ethnohistory | volume =54 | number =3 | year =2007 | pages = 373\u2013406 | doi=10.1215/00141801-2007-001}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://quod.lib.umich.edu/a/anthro1ic?size=20;sort=archsitename;start=1;type=boolean;view=reslist;rgn1=archsitename;select1=all;q1=Moccasin Images of Moccasin Bluff site and artifacts]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Michigan}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Berrien County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites on the National Register of Historic Places in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Late Woodland period]]\n[[Category:Potawatomi]]\n[[Category:Miami tribe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP\n  | name = Moccasin Bluff Site\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = Moccasin Bluff Site.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= Red Bud Trail near [[Buchanan, Michigan]]<ref>The NRIS lists the Moccasin Bluff Site as \"Address Restricted.\" However, the State of Michigan has erected a historical marker at the site ([http://www.michmarkers.com/startup.asp?startpage=L1437.htm Moccasin Bluff] from MichMarkers.org).</ref>\n  | coordinates = {{coord|41|51|20|N|86|22|0|W|region:US-MI_type:railwaystation|display=inline,title}}\n  | locmapin = Michigan#USA\n  | architect OR builder = \n  | architecture = \n  | added = April 13, 1977\n  | area = {{convert|5|acre}}\n  | refnum = 77000710<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Moccasin Bluff Site''' (also designated '''20BE8''') is an [[archaeological site]] located along Red Bud Trail and the [[St. Joseph River (Lake Michigan)|St. Joseph River]] north of [[Buchanan, Michigan]]. It was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1977<ref name=\"nris\"/>, and has been classified as a multi-component [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] site with the major component dating to the [[Late Woodland]]/[[Upper Mississippian]] period.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n==History==\nThe terrace between Moccasin Bluff and the [[St. Joseph River (Michigan)|St. Joseph River]] was home to temporary camps as early as 6300 B.C.  Around A.D 500, inhabitants here traded with other groups of [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] from [[Illinois]] and [[Indiana]]. By A.D. 1100-1400, more permanent villages were established here, and the residents farmed the local lands.<ref name = \"michmark\">{{citation | title = Traveling Through Time: A Guide to Michigan's Historical Markers  |editor = Laura R. Ashlee | publisher = University of Michigan Press | year = 2005 | isbn = 9780472030668 | page = 42 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Xd-mh9r0zEkC&pg=PA42#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 1820s, European settlers moved into the area to log and farm the land. The US government then adopted a policy of moving the local [[Potawatomi]] out of the area and further west. This bluff is said to be named for Cogomoccasin, leader of one of the nearby displaced Potawatomi villages. <ref name = \"michmark\"/>\n\nIn 1948, the site was excavated by a [[University of Michigan]] team, which found [[pottery]], [[Burial|burials]] and remnants of [[maize]] and storage pits. In 2002, [[Michigan State University]] excavated a wetland area at a lower elevation that had not been previously examined.<ref name = \"lp\"/>\n\n==Description==\nThe Moccasin Bluff Site is located on a terrace along Red Bud Trail. The terrace overlooks a wide bend in the [[St. Joseph River (Michigan)|St. Joseph River]] containing a pair of islands. The site is protected by a half-circle of hills to the north, west and south.<ref name = \"lp\">{{citation | title = Moccasin Bluff a look back at local prehistory | author = Andy Hamilton | newspaper = Niles Daily Star | date = February 23, 2007 | url = http://www.leaderpub.com/2007/02/23/moccasin-bluff-a-look-back-at-local-prehistory/}}</ref>\n\nThe site is significant in being one of the few Prehistoric sites in western [[Michigan]] that have been occupied intensively for a very long period of time.  This has resulted in a rich [[midden]] which yields a large quantity of [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]].  The deposits are not stratified, but the artifacts themselves, supported by [[Radiocarbon date|radiocarbon dates]] and comparison to other sites, are  diagnostic of several periods of Native American [[prehistory]], ranging from c. 8500 BC to the 1600s A.D. or just prior to [[Europe|European]] contact.  The [[Archaic period in the Americas|Archaic]] (c. 8500-1500 BC), [[Early Woodland Period|Early Woodland]] (c. 1500-100 BC) and [[Middle Woodland]] (c. 100BC-500 AD) are represented based on the types of artifacts recovered.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  However, the main occupation was in the [[Late Woodland period]] (c. 500-1500 AD) with evidence of [[Upper Mississippian]] (c. 1000-1500 AD) occupation and/or influence as well.\n\n== Results of 1948 Excavations ==\n\nThe excavations yielded pit features, [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]], animal bone and plant remains.<ref name=\"Bettarel\">{{cite book |last1=Bettarel |first1=Robert Louis and Hale G. Smith |title=The Moccasin Bluff Site and the Woodland Cultures of Southwestern Michigan |date=1973 |publisher=University of Michigan Museum of Anthropology, Anthropological Papers No. 49 |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan}}</ref>\n\n=== Features ===\n\nThere were no trace of [[Dwelling|dwellings]] found at the site.  Nor were there post molds that might have indicated the presence of [[Building|structures]].  The researchers concluded that the lack of structural features may be due to the fact that the main part of the site was destroyed during the construction of the Red Bud Trail Highway.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\nFour feature types were identified; [[Storage pit (archaeology)|storage pits]] (62), [[Fire pit|fire pits]] (17), [[Hearth|hearths]] (19) and smudge pits (2).  Three [[Burial|burials]] were located, of which only one was fully excavated.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\nThe fire pits may have functioned as [[Earth oven|earth ovens]] for the roasting of the [[Nymphaea odorata|white water lily]] [[tuber]].<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  No trace of the tubers were found at the site, but in similar pits at the [[Griesmer Site|Griesmer site]] in northwest [[Indiana]] the carbonized remains of [[Nymphaea odorata|white water lily]] tuber were identified;<ref name=\"Faulkner\">{{cite journal |last1=Faulkner |first1=Charles H. |title=The Late Prehistoric Occupation of Northwestern Indiana: A Study of the Upper Mississippi Cultures of the Kankakee Valley |journal=Prehistory Research Series |date=1972 |volume=V |issue=1 |pages=1-222 |publisher=Indiana Historical Society |location=Indianapolis, Indiana}}</ref> and at the [[Schwerdt Site]] on the [[Kalamazoo River]] in [[Michigan]], the carbonized tubers of a similar water-lily species,  [[American Lotus]], were found in deep roasting pits.<ref name=\"McAllister\">{{cite thesis |last1=McAllister |first1=Paul W. |title=The Schwerdt Site (20AE127) Ceramics: A Berrien Phase Ceramic Assemblage in Allegan County, Michigan |degree = Masters  |date=1980 |publisher=Western Michigan University |location=Kalamazoo |page=23 |url=https://scholarworks.wmich.edu/masters_theses/1886/ |ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nBoth smudge pits contained the carbonized remains of [[maize]].  The contents were analyzed and it was determined to be Eastern Complex [[maize]].  Based on previous ethnographic observation, the researchers concluded the features were used as a smudge to cure hides.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n=== Animal Bone ===\n\nThe main species present at Moccasin Bluff were [[deer]], [[sturgeon]], [[elk]] and [[beaver]].  These bones were not modified into tools like the bone tools described in the Artifacts section below, and may be considered food remains.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n=== Plant Remains ===\n\n[[File:Charred_maize_cobs_from_smudge_pit.jpeg|thumb|right|Charred 8-rowed maize cobs from one of the smudge pits]]\n\nSpecimens of [[wood]] [[charcoal]] from the [[Fire pit|fire pits]] were analyzed and found to be primarily [[oak]], [[hickory]] and [[maple]], reflecting the makeup of the local [[deciduous forest]].  Some carbonized food remains were identified as [[acorn]], [[walnut]], [[Canadian plum]], [[Butternut tree|butternut]] and [[Hickory nut|hickory nut]].  Eastern complex [[maize]] was present in the two smudge pits.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Artifacts ===\n\nThe following types of [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]] were recovered from the site:<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n* [[Pottery]] - No whole or completely reconstructable vessels were found at the site.  Therefore the researchers looked primarily at rim sherds and distinctive body sherds to analyze the pottery. The site yielded 534 analyzable rim sherds representing at least 424 vessels.  These artifacts are discussed in more detail below.\n* [[Stone Tools]] - 1,519 [[stone tools]], tool fragments and [[Lithic flake|flakes]].<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  Also present were [[Hammerstone|hammer]] and [[anvil]] stones, [[Celt (tool)|celts]], and abraiding stones.\n* [[Bone tool|Bone tools]] - present were bone cylinders, beaming tools, [[antler]] tools, bone [[Stitching awl|awls]], [[elk]] [[scapula]] tools and [[turtle]] [[Carapace|carapaces]].  A bone rasp (musical instrument) fragment was present in the Birdsell collection, a group of artifacts from the site donated by a local collector.\n* [[Stone]] [[Pendant|Pendants]] - 2 pieces of stone were recovered with holes punched in the middle and were interpreted as [[pendant|pendants]].\n* [[Tobacco pipe|Pipes]] - 6 pipe fragments or unfinished pipe bowls made out of clay or stone.\n* [[Red Ochre]] - 7 pieces of red ochre were in the [[University of Michigan]] Museum of Anthropology collection from the site.\n\nThe non-pottery artifacts found at an archaeological site can provide useful cultural context as well as a glimpse into the domestic tasks performed at a site; ceremonial or religious activities; recreational activities; and clothing or personal adornment.\n\nSome of the most prominent and diagnostic non-pottery artifacts are presented here in more detail:<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:98%\"\n! Material !! Description !! Image !! Qty !! Function / Use !! Comments / Associations\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Small Triangular Points (aka Madison Points)\n|| [[File:Triangular_projectile_points.jpeg|125px|Triangular projectile points]]\n|| 104 (representing 44% of all chipped stone tools)\n|| Hunting/fishing/warfare\n|| Also known as \u201c[[arrowheads]]\u201d; are thought to be arrow-tips for [[Bow and arrow|bows-and-arrows.]]  The usage of the bow-and-arrow seems to have greatly increased during the [[Late Woodland]], probably as a result of increased conflict.<ref name=\"Mason\">{{cite book |last1=Mason |first1=Ronald J. |title=Great Lakes Archaeology |date=1981 |publisher=Academic Press, Incl. |location=New York, New York}}</ref><ref name=\"Lepper\">{{cite book |last1=Lepper |first1=Bradley T. |title=Ohio Archaeology |date=2005 |publisher=Orange Frazer Press |location=Wilmington, Ohio |edition=4th}}</ref>.  Since there is a large quantity of sturgeon bone at Moccasin Bluff, it is strongly probable that these tools were used in fishing activities.\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Ovate or double pointed blades/knives\n|| \n|| 3\n|| Domestic function / cutting applications\n|| Some show signs of hafting.  Typical of Upper Mississippian sites, particularly Huber and Oneota (Orr Focus)\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Bifacially flaked end scraper\n|| [[File:End_scrapers.jpeg|125px|End scrapers]]\n|| 22\n|| Domestic function / processing wood or hides\n|| Common at Oneota sites, but usually unifacially flaked rather than bifacial\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Drills\n|| [[File:T-shape_drills.jpeg|125px|T-shaped drills]]\n|| 6\n|| Domestic function / processing wood or hides\n|| 3 types are present; double pointed and expanded base, which are both common types; and T-shaped (pictured) which is usually found on Fort Ancient sites\n|-\n| Chipped Stone\n|| Thick \"steep-edge\" blades/scrapers\n|| [[File:Thick,_steep-end_blades-scrapers.jpeg|125px|Thick, steep-end blades-scrapers]]\n|| 53\n|| Domestic function / woodworking\n|| Reported from other Huber sites but not from Oneota\n|-\n| Stone\n|| Abraiding stone\n||\n|| 1\n|| Domestic function / straightening arrow shafts\n|| Considered a typical Oneota trait; also occurs in Fort Ancient culture\n|-\n| Antler\n|| Spatula pieces of antler; Chisel/gouge/scraper\n||\n|| 5\n|| Domestic function / specific use unknown\n|| Made from elk antler.  Not common on sites nearby Moccasin Bluff; has been reported on Whittlesey sites in northern Ohio\n|-\n| Bone\n|| Perforated deer bone (hole punched in the middle)\n|| [[File:Perforated_deer_bone.jpeg|95px|Perforated deer bone]]\n|| 1\n|| Possibly Personal Adornment function / pendant\n|| This type of artifact has been reported from the Fisher site and several Fort Ancient sites\n|-\n| Bone\n|| Elk scapula hoes\n|| [[File:Elk_scapula_hoe.jpeg|125px|Elk scapula hoe]]\n|| 3\n|| Domestic function / Agricultural-horticultural or general digging tool\n|| Common at Huber and Oneota sites; sometimes this tool is made with bison scapula, especially westward toward and west of the Mississippi River; they may have been used to dig out the pit features present at Moccasin Bluff.\n|-\n| Bone\n|| unmodified turtle carapace, Common Box Turtle, possibly used as bowl\n||\n|| 2\n|| Domestic function / could have been used as tobacco tray, serving bowl for food, or general food container\n|| The use of a turtle carapace as a tobacco tray has been documented among historic Central Angonkian tribes\n|-\n| Bone\n|| Bone rasp (musical instrument) fragment\n|| [[File:Bone_rasp_(musical_instrument).jpeg|125px|Bone rasp]]\n|| 1\n|| Ceremonial-Recreational function / entertainment or use at ceremony\n|| Also found at Huber, Whittlesey and Fort Ancient sites\n|-\n| Antler\n|| Grooved antler piece\n|| [[File:Grooved_antler.jpeg|70px|Grooved antler]]\n|| 1\n|| Unknown function\n|| Not common from sites in the area of Moccasin Bluff; reported from the South Park site in northern Ohio\n|-\n| Bone\n|| unmodified deer mandibles\n||\n|| \"unusually large numbers\" according to the site report\n|| Domestic function / used for scraping maize kernels off the cobs\n|| The site report does not state there is any wear on the bones to indicate their usage as a tool; but their presence in large numbers strongly implies it.  At other sites they are an indicator of the presence of maize agriculture.\n|-\n| Stone\n|| Pipe bowl fragments; stemless, vase- or bowl-shaped pipe\n||\n|| 2\n|| Ceremonial-Recreational function / pipe smoking\n|| It has been documented among historic tribes that stemless pipes were used for recreational smoking; ceremonial pipes were stemmed\n|-\n| Stone\n|| Unfinished pipe bowl fragments; stemless, block type\n||\n|| 2\n|| Ceremonial-Recreational function / pipe smoking\n|| Block style pipes are known from Whittlesey and Fort Ancient sites in Ohio\n|-\n| Clay\n|| Pipe fragments; modified tube-shaped \n||\n|| 2\n|| Ceremonial-Recreational function / pipe smoking\n|| This type is known from sites in Wisconsin\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Occupations and Associated Pottery Types ===\n\nArchaeologists often find pottery to be a very useful tool in analyzing a prehistoric culture.  It is usually very plentiful at a site and the details of manufacture and decoration are very sensitive indicators of time, space and culture.\n\n==== [[Middle Woodland]] (c. 100 BC-500 AD) ====\n \nA total of 20 vessels of Havana Ware [[pottery]] was collected in the 1948 excavations.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  The Havana Culture was thought to be a local variant of the main [[Middle Woodland]], which was dominated by the [[Adena culture|Adena]] and [[Hopewell culture|Hopewell]] cultures of the [[Mississippi River Valley|Mississippi]] and [[Ohio River Valley|Ohio River]] Valleys.<ref name=\"Mason\"/> [[Middle Woodland]] cultures are characterized by their large [[burial mounds]], some of which are still visible today; as well as their distinctive [[pottery]] forms, [[ceremonial]] practices, [[Agriculture|agricultural]] activities, and widespread [[Trade network|trade networks]].<ref name=\"Mason\"/><ref name=\"Lepper\"/>\n\n==== [[Late Woodland]] (c. 500 AD-1500 AD) / [[Upper Mississippian culture|Upper Mississipian]] (c. 1000-1500 AD)====\n\nThe [[Late Woodland]] period in the [[Great Lakes]] region was characterized by the introduction of [[maize]] [[agriculture]], which allowed for more efficient food production.  This led to [[Population growth|population increases]] which in turn led to increased competition for resources, resulting in more conflict/[[War|warfare]].  After 1000 AD, there was increased interaction and influence from the [[Mississippian culture|Mississippian]] cultures of the [[Mississippi River Valley]], resulting in the formation of [[Upper Mississippian culture|Upper Mississippian cultures]] in the [[Great Lakes area]].<ref name=\"Mason\"/>   \n\nBased on analysis of the [[Late Woodland]] / [[Upper Mississippian culture|Upper Mississippian]] [[pottery]] collected in the 1948 excavations, 2 distinct types of pottery wares were defined:  [[Late Woodland]] grit-[[Temper (pottery)|tempered]] Moccasin Bluff Ware (327 vessels) and [[Upper Mississippian]] shell-[[Temper (pottery)|tempered]] Berrien Ware (48 vessels).<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n===== Moccasin Bluff Ware (327 vessels) =====\n\n[[File:Moccasin_Bluff_Impressed_Exterior_Lip.jpg|thumb|right|Moccasin Bluff Impressed Exterior Lip rim sherd]]\n[[File:Moccasin_Bluff_Notched_Applique_Strip.jpg|thumb|right|Partially reconstructed vessel of Moccasin Bluff Notched Applique Strip]]\n[[File:Moccasin_Bluff_Plain_Modified_Lip.jpg|thumb|right|Partially reconstructed vessel of Moccasin Bluff Plain Modified Lip]]\n\nMoccasin Bluff Ware is divided into several types, some of which have variants, groups and sub-groups:<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\n* Moccasin Bluff Cordmarked (97 vessels), characterized by [[Cord-marked pottery|cord marked]] surface treatment, subdivided into two varieties, Variety 1a and Variety 1b.  Variety 1b is further subdivided into 6 sub-groups.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Collared (14 vessels), characterized by collared or thickened and sometimes castellated rims, subdivided into 2 subgroups.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Modified Lip (57 vessels), characterized by distinctive rim and lip treatments, divided into 6 sub-groups.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Impressed Exterior Lip (56 vessels), characterized by distinctive rim and lip treatments, divided into 2 sub-groups.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Plain (37 vessels), characterized by a distinctive plain smoothed surface.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> '''Time Period''': [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Plain Modified Lip (36 vessels), characterized by distinctive notches or finger impressions on the rim, combined with a plain smoothed exterior surface, subdivided into 3 sub-groups.  Similar pottery has been found at the [[Dumaw Creek Site|Dumaw Creek]], [[Summer Island Site|Summer Island]] and [[Rock Island II Site|Rock Island II]] sites.  [[Dumaw Creek Site|Dumaw Creek]] and [[Summer Island Site|Summer Island]] have been mentioned as possible [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] [[Potawatomi]] sites, and at [[Rock Island II Site|Rock Island II]], the pottery type [[Bell Site (Wn9), Wisconsin|Bell]] Type II has been demonstrated to be a [[Potawatomi]] pottery type.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/><ref name=\"Quimby\">{{cite journal |last1=Quimby |first1=George Irving |title=The Dumaw Creek Site: A Seventeenth Century Prehistoric Indian Village and Cemetery in Oceana County, Michigan |journal=Fieldiana |date=1966 |volume=56 |issue=1 |pages=1-91}}</ref><ref name=\"Brose\">{{cite book |last1=Brose |first1=David S. |title=The Archaeology of Summer Island: Changing Settlement Patterns in Northern Lake Michigan |date=1970 |publisher=University of Michigan Museum of Anthropology, Anthropological Papers No. 41 |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan}}</ref><ref name=\"Mason2\">{{cite book |last1=Mason |first1=Ronald J. |title=Rock Island: Historical Indian Archaeology in the Northern Lake Michigan Basin |date=1986 |publisher=Kent State University Press |location=Kent, Ohio |edition=MCJA Special Paper No. 6}}</ref>  '''Time Period''': Late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]].  '''Prehistoric Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].  '''Protohistoric/Historic Cultural Affiliation''': unknown, possibly [[Potawatomi]].\n* Moccasin Bluff Notched Applique Strip (20 vessels), characterized by the thickening of the rim by use of an appliqu\u00e9 strip, upon which various design motifs are applied.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  '''Time Period''': Late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]].  '''Prehistoric Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].  '''Protohistoric/Historic Cultural Affiliation''': unknown.\n* Moccasin Bluff Scalloped (10 vessels), characterized by scalloped treatment of the rim edge.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  Pottery of this type has been recovered from the [[Dumaw Creek Site|Dumaw Creek]] and [[Schwerdt Site|Schwerdt]] sites, as well as other west [[Michigan]] sites, where it is suggested it may have been made by the [[Potawatomi]].<ref name=\"Quimby\"/><ref name=\"McAllister\"/>. '''Time Period''': Late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]].    '''Prehistoric Cultural Affiliation''': [[Late Woodland]].  '''Protohistoric/Historic Cultural Affiliation''': unknown, possibly [[Potawatomi]].\n\n===== Berrien Ware (48 vessels) =====\n\n[[File:Berrien_Ware_pottery_-_Groups_2_and_3.jpeg|thumb|right|Berrien Ware pottery, Groups 2 and 3]]\n[[File:Berrien_Ware_-_Group_4.jpeg|thumb|right|Berrien Ware pottery, Group 4]]\n\nThe shell-[[Temper (pottery)|tempered]] Berrien Ware present at the site is divided into 5 subgroups based on shoulder, neck, surface finish and rim and lip attributes, and can be typed according to 2 previously recognized [[Upper Mississippian]] cultures:\n\n* Berrien Ware Subgroups 1, 2 and 3 - The first 3 subgroups have been equated with Huber ware, and are differentiated by shoulder and neck attributes.  Overall the Huber Ware is characterized by shell-[[Temper (pottery)|tempered]] smooth surface pottery which is either undecorated or decorated with incised or trailed lines on the shoulder area.   The Huber cultural area is centered on the [[Chicago]] area and has been recognized as closely related to the [[Oneota]] Aspect in [[Wisconsin]] and surrounding states.<ref name=\"Mason\"/>  It is dated to the late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to the Early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] or [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] period, as it has been found in association with [[Europe|European]] trade goods in some sites (c. A.D. 1400-A.D. 1650, or until [[Europe|European]] contact).<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bluhm |first1=Elaine A. and Allen Liss |title=The Anker Site, in Chicago Area Archaeology |journal=Illinois Archaeological Survey |date=1961 |volume=Bulletin No. 3 |pages=104-112}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bluhm |first1=Elaine A. and Gloria J. Fenner |title=The Oak Forest Site, in Chicago Area Archaeology |journal=Illinois Archaeological Society |date=1961 |volume=Bulletin No. 3 |pages=145-147}}</ref>.  The historic culture behind the Huber [[pottery]] is not known for certain, but the [[Miami people|Miami]] tribe were observed by early [[France|French]] explorers to occupy the area around the southern shore of [[Lake Michigan]] during the [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] to early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] Period.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>  Miniature vessels have also been found within the Huber component at Moccasin Bluff.  These are common at other sites in the area and could be interpreted as \u201ctoy\u201d pots or attempts by young children to practice making pottery.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> '''Time Period''': Late [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]] to [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]].  '''Prehistoric Cultural Affiliation''': [[Upper Mississippian]] Huber.  '''Protohistoric/Historic Cultural Affiliation''': unknown, possibly [[Miami people|Miami]].\n* Berrien Ware Subgroups 4 and 5 - these subgroups have been equated with Fisher ware, which was first described at the Fisher Mound site in northeastern [[Illinois]] near the mouth of the [[Illinois River]].<ref name=\"Langford\">{{cite journal |last1=Langford |first1=George |title=The Fisher Mound Group, Successive Aboriginal Occupations near the Mouth of the Illinois River |journal=American Anthropologist |date=1927 |volume=29 |issue=3 |pages=153-206}}</ref>  Like Huber, Fisher is also closely related to the Oneota Aspect.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/><ref name=\"Mason\"/>  Fisher pottery is characterized by shell [[Temper (pottery)|tempering]], predominantly [[Cord-marked pottery|cordmarked]] surfaces, trailed or incised decoration and straight, excurved or flaring rims. Notched lips and rim lugs are also common.  Fisher and Huber seem to overlap spacially, as both cultures have been noted in the [[Chicago]] and northwest [[Indiana]] regions, sometimes at the same site.  The Fisher pottery at Moccasin Bluff is similar to the types Fifield Trailed and Fifield Bold, defined at the [[Fifield Site|Fifield]] site, a Fisher village site in northwestern [[Indiana]].<ref name=\"Faulkner\"/>.  Unlike the Huber Ware, Fisher has never been found associated with Protohistoric or early Historic Period sites and is therefore thought to be slightly older than Huber.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> '''Time Period:''' [[Prehistory|Prehistoric]].  '''Cultural Affiliation''': [[Upper Mississippian]] Fisher.\n\n===== Proposed Late Prehistoric Chronology =====\n\nThe large quantity of [[pottery]] collected at the Moccasin Bluff site, in conjunction with comparisons with other sites, enabled the authors of the site report to propose a chronological history of [[Late Woodland]] cultures in the western [[Michigan]] / northwest [[Indiana]] region.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:77%\"\n! Phase !! Date Range !! Description\n|-\n| Brems Phase\n|| c. 500-1050 A.D.\n|| Associated pottery types: Moccasin Bluff Modified Lip and Moccasin Bluff Collared\n|-\n| Moccasin Bluff Phase\n|| c. 1050-1400 A.D.\n|| Associated pottery types: Moccasin Bluff Impressed Exterior Lip, Berrien Ware Subgroups 4-5 (Fisher Ware)\n|-\n| Berrien Phase\n|| c. 1400-1650 or first European contact\n|| Associated pottery types: Berrien Ware Subgroups 1-3 (Huber Ware), Moccasin Bluff Plain Modified Lip, Moccasin Bluff Notched Applique Strip and Moccasin Bluff Scalloped.  This Phase has been dated at Moccasin Bluff by 2 [[Radiocarbon date|radiocarbon dates]] of A.D. 1590 and A.D. 1640.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n|-\n|}\n\nThe Berrien Phase terminates with the end of [[Prehistory]] and the beginning of the [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] period.  The authors of the site report hypothesize that Berrien-Huber ware may be associated with the historic [[Miami tribe|Miami]] tribe; the Moccasin Bluff Scalloped with an [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]]-speaking tribe such as the [[Potawatomi]]; and the Moccasin Bluff Notched Applique Strip with [[Ohio]] tribes who may have been displaced during the [[Iroquois Wars]].<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> Based on the fact that [[Michigan]] was traditionally considered the homeland of the [[Potawatomi]], other researchers have also suggested that the Berrien Phase represents the material culture of the [[Potawatomi]] tribe.<ref name=\"Cremin\">{{cite book |last1=Cremin |first1=William M. |editor1-last=Holman |editor1-first=Margaret B., Janet G. Brashler and Kathryn E. Parker |title=The Berrien Phase of Southwest Michigan: Proto-Potawatomi?, in Investigating the Archaeological Record of the Great Lakes State: Essays in Honor of Elizabeth Baldwin Garland |date=1996 |publisher=New Issues Press |location=Kalamazoo, Michigan}}</ref>\n\nNotably, there are no [[Europe|European]] trade goods present in the Berrien Phase at Moccasin Bluff.  Therefore the site was abandoned at or just before the time of [[Europe|European]] contact.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/> The same may be said for the Berrien Phase component at the nearby [[Schwerdt Site|Schwerdt]] site.<ref name=\"McAllister\"/> The reason for this may be that in the [[Protohistory|Protohistoric]] or early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] period the [[Potawatomi]] were displaced from western Michigan as a result of the [[Iroquois Wars]] and moved to the west shore of [[Lake Michigan]] into [[Wisconsin]].<ref name=\"Cremin\"/>  The [[Rock Island II Site]] on [[Rock Island, Wisconsin|Rock Island]] in [[Green Bay (Lake Michigan)|Green Bay]], northern [[Lake Michigan]] in [[Wisconsin]] is a good example of a [[Potawatomi]] village in this early [[Historical archaeology|Historic]] period.<ref name=\"Mason2\"/> As a result, the lower peninsula of Michigan became a \"no-mans land\", mostly unoccupied for several decades.<ref name=\"Cremin\"/>\n\n== Results of 2002 Excavations ==\n\nFurther excavations were conducted in 2002 to further clarify questions about the [[Subsistence economy|subsistence]] patterns and site function.<ref name=\"myth\">{{cite journal |last1=O'Gorman |first1=Jodie |title=The Myth of Moccasin Bluff: Rethinking the Potawatomi Pattern |journal=Ethnohistory |date=2007 |volume=54 |issue=3 |pages=373-406}}</ref><ref name=\"O'Gorman\">{{cite journal |last1=O'Gorman |first1=Jodie |title=Revisiting the Moccasin Bluff Site |journal=Michigan Archaeologist |date=2003 |volume=49 |issue=1-2 |pages=7-38}}</ref>  Further examples of Moccasin Bluff Ware were recovered; Moccasin Bluff Plain Modified Lip, Moccasin Bluff Impressed Exterior Lip, Moccasin Bluff Scalloped, Moccasin Bluff [[Cord-marked pottery|Cordmarked]], and Moccasin Bluff Plain.<ref name=\"O'Gorman\"/>  In addition, there were vessels recovered from the [[Middle Woodland]] and also a partially reconstructed vessel from the [[Early Woodland Period|Early Woodland]], a poorly represented time period in the 1948 excavations.<ref name=\"O'Gorman\"/>\n\nThe 2002 excavations used the [[Flotation (archaeology)|flotation]] technique to recover small plant remains, a practice that was not used in earlier times.  As a result, numerous small seeds and fruit seeds were recovered.  Of the fruits, [[pin cherry]], [[pokeberry]], [[grape]] and [[blackberry]]/[[raspberry]] were present.  Of the seeds, several indigenous starchy and oily seed were recovered, including [[goosefoot]], [[maygrass]], [[knotweed]], [[amaranth]], [[sumpweed]], and [[sunflower].  These seeds are part of the [[Eastern Agricultural Complex]], a group of cultivated or semi-cultivated plants utilized by the Prehistoric populations in addition to the better-known crops such as [[maize]], [[Bean|beans]] and [[Cucurbita|squash]]. These types of small seeds are not likely to be recovered unless [[Flotation (archaeology)|flotation]] is used, which is why they were underreported and largely unknown until [[Flotation (archaeology)|flotation]] [[Sampling (statistics)|sampling]] became widespread among [[Archaeology|archaeologists]].<ref name=\"O'Gorman\"/>\n\n== Site function and Berrien Phase settlement patterns ==\n\nThe data recovered from the Moccasin Bluff site shows many indications that the site was occupied for most or all of the year:\n\n* Maize was present at the site, implying it was planted in the spring and harvested in the fall; the presence of numerous deer mandibles implies processing of maize at the site\n* The sturgeon spawning run is in the spring, indicating spring occupation\n* Nutshell was present, indicating a fall occupation\n* Deer may be taken at any time of the year, but in the fall they are at their maximum weight and have grown thicker coats.  The early Historic Native American tribes were observed to have an annual fall deer hunt in which the deer were \"driven\" and killed in mass.\n* Numerous storage pits were present, implying food was stored over the winter\n\nBased on evidence from the excavations, combined with evidence from the early Historic Native American tribes, it was concluded that the Moccasin Bluff site represented a permanent or semi-permanent site, with other sites such as Schwerdt serving as temporary encampments to exploit seasonal resources.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fitting |first1=James E. and Charles E. Cleland |title=Late Prehistoric Settlement Patterns in the Upper Great Lakes |journal=Ethnohistory |date=1969 |volume=16 |issue=4 |pages=289-302}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Cleland |first1=Charles E. |title=Prehistoric Animal Ecology and Ethnozoology of the Upper Great Lakes Region |date=1966 |publisher=University of Michigan |location=Ann Arbor, Michigan |edition=Museum of Anthropology Anthropological Papers no. 29}}</ref>  There are no structures reported from Moccasin Bluff, but the researchers felt that the part of the site containing the houses was destroyed in the building of a highway through the area.<ref name=\"Bettarel\"/>\n\nThe 2002 excavations found no additional evidence of [[maize]] and still no evidence of structures, and some archaeologists are re-thinking the agricultural village interpretation.  Since there is a lack of known [[Late Woodland]] or [[Upper Mississippian culture|Upper Mississippian]] [[protohistoric]] village sites elsewhere in western [[Michigan]], some researchers are suggesting that perhaps the resources available in the area simply did not support large villages and thus, small occupations and encampments were the norm until [[Europe|European]] contact times.<ref name=\"O'Gorman\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{citation | author1 = Robert Louis Bettarel | author2 = Hale Gilliam Smith | title = The Moccasin Bluff site and the Woodland cultures of southwestern Michigan | year =1973}}\n*{{citation | author = Jodie A. O'Gorman | title = The myth of Moccasin Bluff: rethinking the Potawatomi pattern | journal = Ethnohistory | volume =54 | number =3 | year =2007 | pages = 373\u2013406 | doi=10.1215/00141801-2007-001}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://quod.lib.umich.edu/a/anthro1ic?size=20;sort=archsitename;start=1;type=boolean;view=reslist;rgn1=archsitename;select1=all;q1=Moccasin Images of Moccasin Bluff site and artifacts]\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in Michigan}}\n\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Berrien County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites on the National Register of Historic Places in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Late Woodland period]]\n[[Category:Potawatomi]]\n[[Category:Miami people]]\n", "